{"term":"1956","caseName":"Rayonier Incorporated v. United States","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1956/45","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument, Part 1: Rayonier Incorporated v. United States - December 04, 1956 (45)","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren4/oral_argument_audio/13171","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Number 45, Rayonier Incorporated -- Incorporation, Petitioner, versus United States of America.","start":0,"stop":11.476,"duration":11.48},{"text":"Mr. Marion.","start":11.476,"stop":17,"duration":5.52}]},{"speakerName":"Lucien F. Marion","textObjs":[{"text":"May it please this Honorable Court.","start":17,"stop":20.124,"duration":3.12},{"text":"This is a suit under the Federal Tort Claims Act asking for damages caused by a forest fire in 1951 which damages are alleged to have been caused by the negligence of the Forest Service.","start":20.124,"stop":38.555,"duration":18.43},{"text":"I might call Your Honors attention at this point that the fact that Number 47 which follows this case immediately is a companion suit being by other plaintiffs arising out of the same fire.","start":38.555,"stop":52.125,"duration":13.57},{"text":"The case is here on a challenge to the sufficiency of the complaint to state facts upon which a claim may be based.","start":52.125,"stop":59.472,"duration":7.35},{"text":"The District Judge in Tacoma held that they sustained a motion to dismiss and the Court of Appeals affirmed.","start":59.472,"stop":71.777,"duration":12.31},{"text":"Under the circumstances, all of the allegations of the complaint must be accepted as true and construed in a light, the most favorable plaintiff.","start":71.777,"stop":82.926,"duration":11.15},{"text":"Federal Tort Claims Act makes the United States liable for the negligent acts and omissions of its employees under circumstances where the United States if a private individual would be liable claimant under the law of the place where the acts and omissions occurred.","start":82.926,"stop":105.108,"duration":22.18},{"text":"Section 2680 of Title 28 contains the exceptions to the waiver of the immunity.","start":105.108,"stop":114.168,"duration":9.06},{"text":"No one of those exceptions is here involved nor urged by the Government.","start":114.168,"stop":119.353,"duration":5.18},{"text":"Particularly, the discretionary function exception is not involved, as all acts and omissions complained of were at the operational level.","start":119.353,"stop":131.888,"duration":12.54},{"text":"It has been helpful to us in our consideration of this case and in our presentation of it to ask ourselves this question and I offer it because I think it will also be helpful to Your Honors.","start":131.888,"stop":147.496,"duration":15.61},{"text":"Let us assume that the facts here were exactly transposed that the United States with the plaintiff, that Rayonier Incorporated was the defendant that the acts and omissions complained of were those of Rayonier.","start":147.496,"stop":166.432,"duration":18.94},{"text":"Is there any reason in fact or in law why the positions could not be transposed in all material respects?","start":166.432,"stop":173.99,"duration":7.56},{"text":"And if so, would Rayonier be liable to the Government?","start":173.99,"stop":178.771,"duration":4.78},{"text":"Since Rayonier, he's a private individual.","start":178.771,"stop":181.246,"duration":2.48},{"text":"Then if it would be liable, it would follow that -- by that test, the United States is liable.","start":181.246,"stop":189.473,"duration":8.23},{"text":"This fire started on the Olympic Peninsula on August 6, 1951.","start":189.473,"stop":196.654,"duration":7.18},{"text":"It started on land which the defendant owned, had control of and free of unrestricted access to.","start":196.654,"stop":204.909,"duration":8.25},{"text":"These are the allegations of the complaint which I am now recounting.","start":204.909,"stop":210.963,"duration":6.05},{"text":"It started when fire or sparks were thrown from the passing locomotive into accumulations of inflammables on the right of way in the adjoining property, both Government owned and controlled.","start":210.963,"stop":224.907,"duration":13.94},{"text":"It -- from the spot far stage, it spread to a 60 -- 60-acre carrier were it was controlled for about a day and then jumped into a large area of cut-off logged-off lands about 1600 acres in area.","start":224.907,"stop":245.265,"duration":20.36},{"text":"It was contained and controlled in that 1600-acre area on August 11th.","start":245.265,"stop":252.494,"duration":7.23},{"text":"It continued to burn in a small reform in this logged-off area until the early morning hours of September 20th.","start":252.494,"stop":262.824,"duration":10.33},{"text":"In the early morning hours on that day, I think around two or three, winds carried as far south of the 1600-acre area into a joining slash, young growth and virgin timber.","start":262.824,"stop":281.057,"duration":18.23},{"text":"That caused the fire which burned an area, roughly 20 miles in an east-west direction and up to five miles in a north-south direction.","start":281.057,"stop":291.673,"duration":10.62},{"text":"After the fire broke away on the 20th of September, there was nothing anybody could do about it and no negligence is claimed from that occasion on.","start":291.673,"stop":304.278,"duration":12.61},{"text":"Negligence is asserted on behalf of the -- on the part of the Forest Service, both before the fire ever started because of the fire hazardous conditions and practices carried on, on this Government owned and controlled land.","start":304.278,"stop":320.905,"duration":16.63},{"text":"Negligence is claimed and failure to eliminate or extinguish the fire immediately in the spot fire stage, again at the 60-acre stage and again during the 1600-acre stage.","start":320.905,"stop":335.632,"duration":14.73},{"text":"There were adequate men and equipment and water available at all times to extinguish the fire, the Forest Service, and let's say this too.","start":335.632,"stop":349.574,"duration":13.94},{"text":"Immediately, upon the outbreak of the fire on August 6th, the Forest Service was notified.","start":349.574,"stop":356.222,"duration":6.65},{"text":"They immediately stepped in, assumed supervision, direction and control of the fire fighting at all times thereafter.","start":356.222,"stop":366.161,"duration":9.94},{"text":"But during this whole period from August 6 to September 20th, the Forest Service actively took part in the supervision, direction and control of the fire fighting activities.","start":366.161,"stop":380.029,"duration":13.87},{"text":"This was known to petitioner and others in the area.","start":380.029,"stop":384.201,"duration":4.17},{"text":"And the petitioner and others relied upon the Forest Service having been induced to rely upon by their announced position and relied upon the Forest Service to conduct its chore in a prudent manner.","start":384.201,"stop":403.087,"duration":18.89},{"text":"It is highly important, Your Honors, that you have in mind at all times the importance of the practical operation and the physical facts here.","start":403.087,"stop":417.279,"duration":14.19},{"text":"I am somewhat concerned that the Court of Appeals apparently did not appreciate the significance of it and its importance in the part that the Forest Service plays here and the character of its activities.","start":417.279,"stop":434.056,"duration":16.78},{"text":"First, have in mind that this forested area on the Olympic Peninsula is vast in timber and vast areas of cutover lands and that the Government is by far the largest owner.","start":434.056,"stop":451.348,"duration":17.29},{"text":"The Government's ownerships are scattered throughout and intermingled with private ownerships, so that you cannot go very far in one direction up there without running into government land and government timber which is under the jurisdiction of the Forest Service.","start":451.348,"stop":472.877,"duration":21.53},{"text":"The Forest Service and the private timber operators there are essentially in the same business that is the timber business.","start":472.877,"stop":487.704,"duration":14.83},{"text":"The complaint alleges this timber was held by the Government with pecuniary gain and profit.It is sold by the -- under Forest Service jurisdiction to private enterprise.","start":487.704,"stop":500.862,"duration":13.16},{"text":"A large part of the Forest Service activities, in fact, the bulk of it has to do with the development of timber sales, necessary appraisals, the conduct of sales, the engineering required in laying out the sales, laying out roads, conducting the sales and then supervising the logging of the timber in the course of those sales and the construction of roads and so on.","start":500.862,"stop":529.397,"duration":28.54},{"text":"Forest Service also has other duties such as they maintain some forest camps.","start":529.397,"stop":535.462,"duration":6.06},{"text":"They give information to recreations and so on.","start":535.462,"stop":541.073,"duration":5.61},{"text":"Now, the Forest Service in common with all the other timber operators there are naturally concerned about the fire.","start":541.073,"stop":552.978,"duration":11.9},{"text":"The Forest Service, however, just like the timber operators, does not in itself maintain a fire department.","start":552.978,"stop":562.619,"duration":9.64},{"text":"It has relatively few employees, relatively little equipment and neither the Forest Service nor any other operator has sufficient equipment or men of which to cope with a major fire.","start":562.619,"stop":580.194,"duration":17.57},{"text":"However, because of this, the Forest Service and the private industries recognized that cooperation is necessary.","start":580.194,"stop":590.098,"duration":9.9},{"text":"If I own a track of timber here, I am concerned that fire, about any fire starting on my land or immediately close to my land which threatens my timber.","start":590.098,"stop":604.289,"duration":14.19},{"text":"We recognized that it would be uneconomical for each to maintain a complete fire department and it is not necessary because in that area where the timber industries are the main source of livelihood, everyone will respond willingly, men will serve in fire fighting activities, people will furnish their equipment.","start":604.289,"stop":632.519,"duration":28.23},{"text":"Now, to carry out this battle against the common enemy, both the Forest Service and private industries have what they call a fire suppression plan.","start":632.519,"stop":647.147,"duration":14.63},{"text":"That fire suppression plan contains a list of the persons available to fight fires, the equipment to available to fight fires and how those persons can be reached and brought to the scene of the fire.","start":647.147,"stop":661.475,"duration":14.33},{"text":"That is the type of plan of the Forest Service has.","start":661.475,"stop":667.582,"duration":6.11}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that joined in by the private owners?","start":667.582,"stop":673.46,"duration":5.88}]},{"speakerName":"Lucien F. Marion","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, it's not a matter of joining in.","start":673.46,"stop":676.379,"duration":2.92},{"text":"I mean Rayonier will have a list of Forest Service employees.","start":676.379,"stop":680.987,"duration":4.61},{"text":"It will have a list of ex-company's employees and so and so, (Inaudible) contractors and employees and the list of their equipment where they're located.","start":680.987,"stop":691.14,"duration":10.15},{"text":"It occur -- fire occurs on Rayonier's land, Rayonier will step in --","start":691.14,"stop":694.468,"duration":3.33}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But there's no -- there's no association of (Voice Overlap) --","start":694.468,"stop":696.913,"duration":2.45}]},{"speakerName":"Lucien F. Marion","textObjs":[{"text":"There's no association, Your Honor.","start":696.913,"stop":700.037,"duration":3.12},{"text":"The point is that if Rayonier were party on this land as the fire had started, Rayonier would send its men there and they would take charge and they would direct it.","start":700.037,"stop":710.556,"duration":10.52},{"text":"And they would follow Rayonier's plan to call in all the men and equipment from our neighbors as well as our own to supervise this and fight it.","start":710.556,"stop":721.621,"duration":11.06},{"text":"And that is the case with the Forest Service here.","start":721.621,"stop":725.711,"duration":4.09},{"text":"Those are the facts.","start":725.711,"stop":727.416,"duration":1.71},{"text":"It's this forest.","start":727.416,"stop":729.42,"duration":2},{"text":"There is this fire suppression plan and the fact that they do not maintain a fire department.","start":729.42,"stop":736.514,"duration":7.09},{"text":"Let me also point out that under the statute, 16 United States Code 5 -- 51, I believe, it is cited in our brief.","start":736.514,"stop":747.055,"duration":10.54},{"text":"The Forest Service is authorized to engage in fire or to take steps necessary to protect the public forest from fire depredation.","start":747.055,"stop":757.594,"duration":10.54},{"text":"No place in the statutes to refine their authorization to maintain a fire department for the public at large.","start":757.594,"stop":766.204,"duration":8.61},{"text":"Forest Service is also authorized to cooperate with the State and private industries.","start":766.204,"stop":771.891,"duration":5.69},{"text":"But the cooperation which I have just described, which is necessary, and that's the basis for this so-called cooperation.","start":771.891,"stop":782.307,"duration":10.42},{"text":"May I also point out that the State of Washington has sets standards of good forestry practices for private industries and all timber owners, those standards being reflected both from the statutes and common law and they prescribed certain minimum standards to reduce, eliminate or minimize the fire hazard in forest areas.","start":782.307,"stop":808.912,"duration":26.61},{"text":"Those standards may to a stranger seem high but they obviously are not because the timber industry has operated successfully under them for some 70 years.","start":808.912,"stop":824.312,"duration":15.4},{"text":"Now, this brings us to -- with that factual background, Your Honors, District Judge Boldt --","start":824.312,"stop":833.559,"duration":9.25}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what -- what do those standards that are applicable here?","start":833.559,"stop":836.421,"duration":2.86}]},{"speakerName":"Lucien F. Marion","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, they say that it should be unlawful to permit accumulations of land clearing or logging debris, slash on your land to be --","start":836.421,"stop":848.039,"duration":11.62}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Are those applicable to this case?","start":848.039,"stop":850.582,"duration":2.54}]},{"speakerName":"Lucien F. Marion","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":850.582,"stop":853.344,"duration":2.76},{"text":"There are a number of standards, also the operation of trains without certain training --","start":853.344,"stop":859.989,"duration":6.64}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Operations of what?","start":859.989,"stop":861.344,"duration":1.36}]},{"speakerName":"Lucien F. Marion","textObjs":[{"text":"Trains, locomotives.","start":861.344,"stop":864.169,"duration":2.82}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Is it your position, Mr. Marion, that -- that anyone who joins in, in the fighting of these fires is liable for any -- to help his neighbors is liable for any negligent manner in which he fights the fire?","start":864.169,"stop":879.995,"duration":15.83}]},{"speakerName":"Lucien F. Marion","textObjs":[{"text":"Gracious no, Your Honor.","start":879.995,"stop":882.181,"duration":2.19},{"text":"No, sir.","start":882.181,"stop":883.417,"duration":1.24},{"text":"But if I step in to fight a fire and I may have responsibilities for fighting that fire starting from several sources, if I step in, undertake the act and assumed direction and control, then -- and I induce reliance upon my assumed position then I am bound to that course of conduct which any man in that position is bound.","start":883.417,"stop":911.617,"duration":28.2},{"text":"There's one other factual thing about which --","start":911.617,"stop":913.561,"duration":1.94}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what is this?","start":913.561,"stop":914.589,"duration":1.03},{"text":"If it is, there's liability assumed under this loose arrangement you have here of all your neighbors coming to your assistance or mutual aid -- aid program.","start":914.589,"stop":927.542,"duration":12.95},{"text":"And suppose under -- under that any given situation, one man takes a leadership and -- and it takes to organize the firefighters.","start":927.542,"stop":941.94,"duration":14.4},{"text":"He does something in a negligent manner.","start":941.94,"stop":943.794,"duration":1.85},{"text":"Is he liable for -- for the results of his negligence?","start":943.794,"stop":948.577,"duration":4.78}]},{"speakerName":"Lucien F. Marion","textObjs":[{"text":"I say yes, he is and no -- no reason why he should not be.","start":948.577,"stop":954.166,"duration":5.59}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And if he fails to come when you call for him, he is liable in your view?","start":954.166,"stop":958.879,"duration":4.71}]},{"speakerName":"Lucien F. Marion","textObjs":[{"text":"There is no duty to respond to a call by someone, Your Honor.","start":958.879,"stop":961.901,"duration":3.02}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Only if does respond then he must make no errors.","start":961.901,"stop":967.388,"duration":5.49}]},{"speakerName":"Lucien F. Marion","textObjs":[{"text":"He is bound by -- that same guides of prudent conduct as anyone else.","start":967.388,"stop":972.836,"duration":5.45},{"text":"We must not be confused here, Your Honor, in the -- what might be negligence under emergent conditions.","start":972.836,"stop":980.999,"duration":8.16},{"text":"That's not involved here.","start":980.999,"stop":983.811,"duration":2.81},{"text":"And in that connection, I wish also to point this out to Your Honors.","start":983.811,"stop":989.261,"duration":5.45},{"text":"For the 40 days and 40 nights during which this fire burned the 1600-acre area, there was hardly any rain.","start":989.261,"stop":999.029,"duration":9.77},{"text":"In fact, there had been -- in fact, there's no rain for period of 4 months prior to that time.","start":999.029,"stop":1005.195,"duration":6.17},{"text":"During that period of time, Forest Service took no effort to seek out and extinguish the fire.","start":1005.195,"stop":1014.424,"duration":9.23},{"text":"Although, it was known that in these dry periods, the prevailing winds are northeasterly, they are dry winds, the humidity was low and in the lee of this 1600-acre area were all these vast stands of virgin timber which are endangered by any fire not properly handled.","start":1014.424,"stop":1040.963,"duration":26.54},{"text":"This was maintained by the district ranger only on a patrol basis and only during the daytime.","start":1040.963,"stop":1047.53,"duration":6.57},{"text":"After the normal quitting time of the day, there was no one on duty watching this area.","start":1047.53,"stop":1054.035,"duration":6.51},{"text":"Also, it is significant that just one week before the breakaway on September 20th, fire actually did blow out of the sparks in this area and jumped the fire alarms.","start":1054.035,"stop":1064.938,"duration":10.9},{"text":"That it so happened, there were men on duty at that time and they were able to extinguish that fire.","start":1064.938,"stop":1070.395,"duration":5.46},{"text":"All of these conditions and situations were known to the district ranger.","start":1070.395,"stop":1075.464,"duration":5.07},{"text":"The consequences were foreseeable.","start":1075.464,"stop":1080.282,"duration":4.82},{"text":"Now Your Honors, District Judge Boldt had before him at this time, the case of Dalehite versus United States decided in 1953.","start":1080.282,"stop":1091.998,"duration":11.72},{"text":"It was greatly perplexed and said before that case, he would hold a complaint sufficient to state the cause of action.","start":1091.998,"stop":1099.214,"duration":7.22},{"text":"He reasoned this way.","start":1099.214,"stop":1100.871,"duration":1.66},{"text":"His Forest Service employees are employees of the Government.","start":1100.871,"stop":1103.845,"duration":2.97},{"text":"Therefore, they are public employees.","start":1103.845,"stop":1106.2,"duration":2.36},{"text":"They were fighting fire.","start":1106.2,"stop":1107.534,"duration":1.33},{"text":"Therefore, they were public firemen.","start":1107.534,"stop":1111.676,"duration":4.14},{"text":"The Court of Appeals likewise rested its decision upon the Dalehite case in most respects.","start":1111.676,"stop":1121.214,"duration":9.54},{"text":"I want to urge upon, Your Honors --","start":1121.214,"stop":1122.869,"duration":1.65}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"They made some preliminary conclusion, didn't it, under state law?","start":1122.869,"stop":1127.687,"duration":4.82}]},{"speakerName":"Lucien F. Marion","textObjs":[{"text":"I beg your pardon?","start":1127.687,"stop":1128.496,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"They say it made some preliminary conclusions under state law.","start":1128.496,"stop":1135.63,"duration":7.13}]},{"speakerName":"Lucien F. Marion","textObjs":[{"text":"It deals with other facets of this under state law, Your Honor.","start":1135.63,"stop":1141.466,"duration":5.84}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"What I'm suggesting is that if the conclusions had been different as to the duty of the United States under a state law by -- the Forest Service, liability might have been predicated without getting into the Dalehite problem at all, might it not?","start":1141.466,"stop":1165.396,"duration":23.93}]},{"speakerName":"Lucien F. Marion","textObjs":[{"text":"Not as I read the opinion of the Court of Appeals, Your Honor, and I had not intended to get into that phase but -- but I would like to say this.","start":1165.396,"stop":1174.535,"duration":9.14},{"text":"That under the reasoning of the Court of Appeals, they assumed that -- had there been negligence in their duty under state law because of these conditions prior to the fire and the conduct before the breakaway.","start":1174.535,"stop":1191.498,"duration":16.96},{"text":"The Court of Appeals said in effect that even though there'd be negligence in the Forest Service at that point, they become immune from such -- from liability for subsequent negligence by putting on their firemen's hats and proceeding then from the status of public firemen.","start":1191.498,"stop":1209.717,"duration":18.22},{"text":"I wish to point out and urge the reason why Dalehite is not applicable in the first instance.","start":1209.717,"stop":1217.408,"duration":7.69},{"text":"There, the Coast Guard was charged apparently with negligence, precise nature which is not clear from the opinions.","start":1217.408,"stop":1228.317,"duration":10.91},{"text":"But at any rate, it is clear that the Coast Guard did not supervise or undertake the direction of the fire fighting at the Texas City fire or did they induce reliance on others that they would so fight the fire or supervise it and act prudently.","start":1228.317,"stop":1245.725,"duration":17.41},{"text":"The local authorities there were in charge of the fire.","start":1245.725,"stop":1248.909,"duration":3.18},{"text":"In the case at bar, the Forest Service was the actor.","start":1248.909,"stop":1252.761,"duration":3.85},{"text":"It did take over supervision and did induce reliance.","start":1252.761,"stop":1256.82,"duration":4.06},{"text":"Second, in the Dalehite case, there was no government property involved.","start":1256.82,"stop":1261,"duration":4.18}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) -- before or after the breakaway?","start":1261,"stop":1262.723,"duration":1.72}]},{"speakerName":"Lucien F. Marion","textObjs":[{"text":"I beg you pardon.","start":1262.723,"stop":1263.631,"duration":0.91}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Before or after the breakaway?","start":1263.631,"stop":1265.687,"duration":2.06},{"text":"Before the breakaway?","start":1265.687,"stop":1267.783,"duration":2.1}]},{"speakerName":"Lucien F. Marion","textObjs":[{"text":"Forest Service stepped in immediately after the fire started on August 6th, Your Honor, and maintained --","start":1267.783,"stop":1272.11,"duration":4.33}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I mean -- I mean the first fire.","start":1272.11,"stop":1274.104,"duration":1.99}]},{"speakerName":"Lucien F. Marion","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":1274.104,"stop":1275.172,"duration":1.07},{"text":"I mean it's the same fire actually burning --","start":1275.172,"stop":1276.405,"duration":1.23}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Same fire?","start":1276.405,"stop":1277.403,"duration":1},{"text":"The first phase of it?","start":1277.403,"stop":1278.092,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"Lucien F. Marion","textObjs":[{"text":"At the first phase of it on August 6th when it broke out, that is when the Forest Service stepped in and it continued in that role at all times thereafter.","start":1278.092,"stop":1287.911,"duration":9.82},{"text":"In Dalehite, there was no government property involved.","start":1287.911,"stop":1291.225,"duration":3.31},{"text":"No government ships on fire, no government docks, whereas in the case at bar, the Forest Service participation in fire fighting was directly associated with the ownership of government timber and was for the direct benefit of the timber.","start":1291.225,"stop":1309.914,"duration":18.69},{"text":"Thirdly, as we read the Dalehite case, there was no duty established on the Coast Guard and duty is an essential element of actionable negligence.","start":1309.914,"stop":1320.729,"duration":10.82},{"text":"Whereas in the case at bar, the Forest Service had duties standing from several sources including that of the actor or volunteer who induces reliance and also as a landowner.","start":1320.729,"stop":1334.72,"duration":13.99},{"text":"Next, in the -- as we understand the Dalehite facts, the Coast Guard do not even get into the act of fire fighting and that it was only about an hour between the time that the fires first broke out in the time of the terrific explosion which caused -- caused the damages.","start":1334.72,"stop":1353.629,"duration":18.91},{"text":"Here, the Forest Service was in this from the beginning.","start":1353.629,"stop":1356.851,"duration":3.22},{"text":"They had adequate time to control the fire.","start":1356.851,"stop":1362.598,"duration":5.75},{"text":"Now lastly, the Forest Service employees were not public firemen.","start":1362.598,"stop":1368.544,"duration":5.95},{"text":"Their duties were associated with the administration of government timber.","start":1368.544,"stop":1372.612,"duration":4.07},{"text":"They had no authority to act, otherwise, and in connections with the administration of government timber.","start":1372.612,"stop":1381.194,"duration":8.58},{"text":"That should be compared to the situation with this public firemen immunity as normally announced and that is the City Fire Departments where they are maintained for the benefit of one and all in the city to protect any persons, all persons and property in the city, not associated with city-owned property.","start":1381.194,"stop":1403.278,"duration":22.08},{"text":"And those cases which the public firemen immunity doctrine is announced.","start":1403.278,"stop":1411.263,"duration":7.98},{"text":"Then they associate that with a governmental function then services for the benefit of the public at large.","start":1411.263,"stop":1420.025,"duration":8.76},{"text":"Now, we come to the influence of the case of Indian Towing Company against the United States decided by this Court about a year ago.","start":1420.025,"stop":1429.059,"duration":9.03}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Marion, I do not like --","start":1429.059,"stop":1429.778,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"Lucien F. Marion","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes?","start":1429.778,"stop":1430.145,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- to interrupt the course of your argument, but perhaps, you can tell me this.","start":1430.145,"stop":1435.203,"duration":5.06},{"text":"I've got issue (Inaudible) that the scope in your brief referring to you and the Government don't come as an issue except the negligence.","start":1435.203,"stop":1445.459,"duration":10.26},{"text":"In other words, you think you have to get Dalehite out of the way.","start":1445.459,"stop":1449.951,"duration":4.49},{"text":"The Government says they don't reach the Dalehite case and talk about Dalehite as they come to it.","start":1449.951,"stop":1454.426,"duration":4.47},{"text":"Now, why is there that difference of conception of the safety controversy in the case?","start":1454.426,"stop":1460.218,"duration":5.79},{"text":"I assume the Government doesn't reach Dalehite which means that the Government is within the exception or limitation of what went on before it (Inaudible) and argues and I take it to have argued extensively in the beginning that it's mainly right.","start":1460.218,"stop":1478.044,"duration":17.83},{"text":"But since you don't reach Dalehite, you on the other hand, since you have to get Dalehite out -- off the track and then you have a clear -- a clear overhead.","start":1478.044,"stop":1487.802,"duration":9.76},{"text":"I'm adverting to the question that I think is explicit (Inaudible) Justice Harlan.","start":1487.802,"stop":1492.451,"duration":4.65},{"text":"I don't mean to have -- in case the course of your argument, but why is that so?","start":1492.451,"stop":1495.992,"duration":3.54},{"text":"Why should there be such an essential difference?","start":1495.992,"stop":1498.625,"duration":2.63},{"text":"I mean (Inaudible) to the Government in view as to what it is we are facing with?","start":1498.625,"stop":1503.882,"duration":5.26}]},{"speakerName":"Lucien F. Marion","textObjs":[{"text":"The reason for the difference, Your Honor, lies in the Government's failure to face up to the factual situation of the status of Forest Service employees and the Government as a property owner here.","start":1503.882,"stop":1522.592,"duration":18.71},{"text":"That -- the facts which I have described in which are contained in the complaint paint that picture.","start":1522.592,"stop":1531.374,"duration":8.78},{"text":"Now, frankly Your Honor, I might disagree with the necessity for the Dalehite pronouncement in connection with the facts of that case.","start":1531.374,"stop":1549.547,"duration":18.17},{"text":"But I do think that the facts are so dissimilar that that is not controlling law in the case at bar.","start":1549.547,"stop":1560.973,"duration":11.43},{"text":"Insofar as the philosophy of the Dalehite case, I've been pronouncing it Dalehite.","start":1560.973,"stop":1567.712,"duration":6.74},{"text":"I don't know which is correct, Your Honor, if you'll excuse me.","start":1567.712,"stop":1570.946,"duration":3.23}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"There is not -- they're the same, which ever it is.","start":1570.946,"stop":1574.547,"duration":3.6}]},{"speakerName":"Lucien F. Marion","textObjs":[{"text":"Correct.","start":1574.547,"stop":1576.102,"duration":1.56},{"text":"Indian Towing, announced by this Court about a year ago, establishes several things which are very pertinent to this case.","start":1576.102,"stop":1584.661,"duration":8.56},{"text":"First, it rejects municipal corporation law as not applicable to the administration of the Federal Tort Claims Act.","start":1584.661,"stop":1595.842,"duration":11.18},{"text":"The public firemen immunity theory is definitely a child of municipal corporation law.","start":1595.842,"stop":1602.028,"duration":6.19},{"text":"It is found nowhere else in the basis of immunity stems from the fact that the cases say that fire fighting is a governmental function.","start":1602.028,"stop":1614.721,"duration":12.69},{"text":"These fire departments are maintained for the benefit of one and all of public's function.","start":1614.721,"stop":1619.32,"duration":4.6},{"text":"From that theory, the city cannot be held on the doctrine of respondeat superior for the negligence of its firemen.","start":1619.32,"stop":1626.491,"duration":7.17},{"text":"Second, Indian Towing establishes that the public function or governmental character of an employee's activities is immaterial.","start":1626.491,"stop":1637.448,"duration":10.96},{"text":"Now, that is consistent with many holdings under the Federal Tort Claims Act and it's hard to justify immunity of the Forest Service as being a public engagement in light of the holdings of liability of the United States for negligence of its employees.","start":1637.448,"stop":1656.641,"duration":19.19},{"text":"And say the conduct of lighthouses, the operation of military vehicles, the operation of military airplanes, operation of airport controlled towers, Coast Guard rescue services, even the classic example cited as the type of thing for which the Government should be liable, namely, the negligence of a male truck driver.","start":1656.641,"stop":1679.983,"duration":23.34},{"text":"That certainly is in a public function or governmental in character.","start":1679.983,"stop":1686.777,"duration":6.79},{"text":"It -- lastly, Indian Towing establishes that where the Government undertakes to act, whether you call it a volunteer, an actor, a good samaritan or by what meaning.","start":1686.777,"stop":1700.576,"duration":13.8},{"text":"If he undertakes to act and induces reliance, he is then bound to act prudently.","start":1700.576,"stop":1707.241,"duration":6.66},{"text":"And if he is negligent in the conduct to that activity, then he must pay for the consequences of his negligence.","start":1707.241,"stop":1715.764,"duration":8.52},{"text":"Now, Your Honors, if we reverse the situation of the parties here and there's no reason why Rayonier might not have found itself and precisely the same situation, then I say, Rayonier would have been liable and I have yet to hear from the Attorney General, to whom we have opposed this question repeatedly, would Rayonier have been liable or not?","start":1715.764,"stop":1738.315,"duration":22.55},{"text":"If it would, then it follows because the Government's liability is the same as Rayonier's would be.","start":1738.315,"stop":1745.451,"duration":7.14},{"text":"It follows that the Government is liable.","start":1745.451,"stop":1748.545,"duration":3.09},{"text":"Of the remaining two minutes I have, Your Honors, I'd like to reserve Mr. Justice.","start":1748.545,"stop":1751.659,"duration":3.11}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"May I ask just --","start":1751.659,"stop":1752.555,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"Lucien F. Marion","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, indeed, sir.","start":1752.555,"stop":1752.723,"duration":0.17}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"-- one question I -- I have a question.","start":1752.723,"stop":1755.076,"duration":2.35},{"text":"I don't know anything.","start":1755.076,"stop":1755.974,"duration":0.9},{"text":"I have here the question that the Forest Service may -- one of its chief responsibilities in fighting the fire or forest fires.","start":1755.974,"stop":1766.692,"duration":10.72}]},{"speakerName":"Lucien F. Marion","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, I --","start":1766.692,"stop":1767.52,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Does that apply to this group that it was during the Forest Service?","start":1767.52,"stop":1772.939,"duration":5.42}]},{"speakerName":"Lucien F. Marion","textObjs":[{"text":"I believe Your Honor's impression is quite incorrect.","start":1772.939,"stop":1777.223,"duration":4.28},{"text":"But the percentage of time, the amount of dollars involved are (Voice Overlap) --","start":1777.223,"stop":1783.88,"duration":6.66}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"What are these (Voice Overlap) -- towers I see around every place where --","start":1783.88,"stop":1787.487,"duration":3.61}]},{"speakerName":"Lucien F. Marion","textObjs":[{"text":"I beg your pardon.","start":1787.487,"stop":1788.296,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"These towers where a man would sit and watch the fires, are they Forest Service?","start":1788.296,"stop":1793.683,"duration":5.39}]},{"speakerName":"Lucien F. Marion","textObjs":[{"text":"They maybe maintained by the Forest Service.","start":1793.683,"stop":1796.019,"duration":2.34},{"text":"They maybe maintained by estates.","start":1796.019,"stop":1798.482,"duration":2.46},{"text":"There are even private watchtowers.","start":1798.482,"stop":1801.766,"duration":3.28}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"You -- you don't consider fire fighting in the forest as one of the essential activities of the Forest Service.","start":1801.766,"stop":1808.81,"duration":7.04}]},{"speakerName":"Lucien F. Marion","textObjs":[{"text":"Not in the sense --","start":1808.81,"stop":1809.457,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Not as a public fireman.","start":1809.457,"stop":1811.611,"duration":2.15}]},{"speakerName":"Lucien F. Marion","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":1811.611,"stop":1812.138,"duration":0.53},{"text":"And their -- their presence there and their activity is not there in the sense which protecting anybody and everybody.","start":1812.138,"stop":1818.932,"duration":6.79},{"text":"And that's the essential part of this mixed ownership as -- as mixed up pattern ownership and the interest which each timber operator has in the same end result.","start":1818.932,"stop":1829.871,"duration":10.94}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I assume it was quite contrary out west of the Forest Service -- I don't know what portion of their budget is devoted to fire fighting but so far as (Inaudible) is a very important function that they formed --","start":1829.871,"stop":1847.724,"duration":17.85}]},{"speakerName":"Lucien F. Marion","textObjs":[{"text":"There's no --","start":1847.724,"stop":1848.261,"duration":0.54}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"-- every forester as if some of them had to (Inaudible)","start":1848.261,"stop":1851.652,"duration":3.39}]},{"speakerName":"Lucien F. Marion","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor, there is no question --","start":1851.652,"stop":1853.169,"duration":1.52}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Drop them in from planes, it's very highly organized.","start":1853.169,"stop":1856.153,"duration":2.98}]},{"speakerName":"Lucien F. Marion","textObjs":[{"text":"It is a -- an important function but it is neither a major function nor is it a function which it performs except in connection with the administration of federal timber.","start":1856.153,"stop":1871.986,"duration":15.83},{"text":"But the necessary cooperation of all timber owners is the essential part.","start":1871.986,"stop":1879.15,"duration":7.16}]},{"speakerName":"Harold Burton","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, you draw the distinction that in between protecting their own grounds from fire and protecting other people's grounds from fire?","start":1879.15,"stop":1886.813,"duration":7.66}]},{"speakerName":"Lucien F. Marion","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I do, Your Honor.","start":1886.813,"stop":1887.619,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"Harold Burton","textObjs":[{"text":"The other fireman insofar as the national forests are concerned but not fireman for keeping at large.","start":1887.619,"stop":1894.171,"duration":6.55}]},{"speakerName":"Lucien F. Marion","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice Burton, their activities are all associated with the administration of federal timber, but that can be done properly only by concerning itself with others just as the other owners concerned themselves with federal timber.","start":1894.171,"stop":1909.17,"duration":15}]},{"speakerName":"Harold Burton","textObjs":[{"text":"But no more.","start":1909.17,"stop":1910.857,"duration":1.69},{"text":"And no more than I would -- I mean they have the same relation to others that others have to them.","start":1910.857,"stop":1917.779,"duration":6.92},{"text":"I mean --","start":1917.779,"stop":1919.136,"duration":1.36}]},{"speakerName":"Lucien F. Marion","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct.","start":1919.136,"stop":1919.945,"duration":0.81},{"text":"Except, federal ownership is so extensive and scattered in so many places that hardly a fire can occur or does not threaten federal timber but private parties themselves.","start":1919.945,"stop":1933.465,"duration":13.52},{"text":"They have been in fight fires.","start":1933.465,"stop":1935.279,"duration":1.81},{"text":"They take over control and it will be the case of Forest Service employees are standing by and watching others to supervise this but lending such help as they maybe called upon.","start":1935.279,"stop":1946.965,"duration":11.69},{"text":"It's completely a reciprocal, cooperative fire department if in the aggregate both public and private employees are to be regardless as a fire department.","start":1946.965,"stop":1959.866,"duration":12.9},{"text":"That's the only way in which they could be so regard it.","start":1959.866,"stop":1963.559,"duration":3.69},{"text":"My time has expired.","start":1963.559,"stop":1964.585,"duration":1.03},{"text":"Thank you, sir.","start":1964.585,"stop":1966.549,"duration":1.96}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Doub.","start":1966.549,"stop":1972.286,"duration":5.74}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"If the Court please.","start":1972.286,"stop":1976.386,"duration":4.1},{"text":"The fire fighting on private lands is explicitly authorized by federal statute.","start":1976.386,"stop":1983.749,"duration":7.36},{"text":"And the reports of the Department of Agriculture show that the Forest Service is fighting -- has been fighting 30 -- between 10,000 and 11,000 independent and separate fires a year.","start":1983.749,"stop":2002.019,"duration":18.27},{"text":"The daily average is 30.","start":2002.019,"stop":2004.29,"duration":2.27},{"text":"And on the basis of that, there are 30 fires being fought today.","start":2004.29,"stop":2009.22,"duration":4.93},{"text":"Now, if the Court please, this case presents clearly for a decision, the major question whether the traditional immunity of public fireman should be applied to the Forest Service of the United States which is in -- in fighting fires on public and private lands.","start":2009.22,"stop":2031.874,"duration":22.65},{"text":"Now, you'll find on page 35, in paragraph 35 of Rayonier's complaint and that's page 26 of the record.","start":2031.874,"stop":2041.624,"duration":9.75},{"text":"There are 15 specifications of negligence and of these 13 alleged negligence by the Forest Service in fighting this fire.","start":2041.624,"stop":2053.772,"duration":12.15},{"text":"So this is a question of national importance and it's raised for the first time here under the Tort Claims Act.","start":2053.772,"stop":2061.764,"duration":7.99},{"text":"Now, the remaining questions, if the Court please, as to the possible liability of the United States as an owner of forest land in permitting its property to be substandard conditions that is not within the public fireman immunity principle.","start":2061.764,"stop":2083.65,"duration":21.89},{"text":"It involves merely the interpretation of local state laws applied to private property owners and -- so the major issue here and the issue that is a particular concerned to the Government is the -- whether Dalehite and the immunity principle established as to the Coast Guard there shall be applied to the Forest Service --","start":2083.65,"stop":2111.081,"duration":27.43}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But if one could find -- but if one finds that Washington Law wouldn't allow recovery against the private sector or -- or non-United States defendants then we don't have to reach this major question on which I can well understand the Government would like to get a ruling but --","start":2111.081,"stop":2129.582,"duration":18.5}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor --","start":2129.582,"stop":2130.021,"duration":0.44}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) -- that satisfies the trial if we're ruling on the court ground that there's an error around it.","start":2130.021,"stop":2135.279,"duration":5.26}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor, we believe that this question is clearly flushed under this pleading.","start":2135.279,"stop":2139.558,"duration":4.28}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Clearly what?","start":2139.558,"stop":2140.367,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"It's clearly flushed here.","start":2140.367,"stop":2142.301,"duration":1.93},{"text":"It's unavoidable and it should be met.","start":2142.301,"stop":2145.515,"duration":3.21}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But if your first part --","start":2145.515,"stop":2145.972,"duration":0.46}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":2145.972,"stop":2146.162,"duration":0.19}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- is (Inaudible) then -- then it is avoidable, it isn't here.","start":2146.162,"stop":2151.11,"duration":4.95}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, perhaps --","start":2151.11,"stop":2151.599,"duration":0.49}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) I don't understand.","start":2151.599,"stop":2153.056,"duration":1.46},{"text":"I've read your brief but I've read your outline, your (Inaudible)","start":2153.056,"stop":2155.908,"duration":2.85}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Pardon.","start":2155.908,"stop":2156.185,"duration":0.28},{"text":"Well, let me proceed --","start":2156.185,"stop":2157.034,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":2157.034,"stop":2157.212,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"-- Your Honor.","start":2157.212,"stop":2157.819,"duration":0.61}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Could I -- before you leave that subject in amplifying what has just been suggested and what I intended to raise from my earlier question from your adversary.","start":2157.819,"stop":2167.018,"duration":9.2},{"text":"This is a thing that puzzles me a little bit.","start":2167.018,"stop":2170.499,"duration":3.48},{"text":"If this fire started on the so-called railroad portion, the railroad easement by sparks flying over into the Government land, right?","start":2170.499,"stop":2183.163,"duration":12.66}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"And so construed by the Court of Appeals.","start":2183.163,"stop":2184.638,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":2184.638,"stop":2185.107,"duration":0.47},{"text":"And one of the counts of negligence was that the Government was responsible from the emission of those sparks from the so-called easement part of the land.","start":2185.107,"stop":2199.268,"duration":14.16}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean from the locomotive stock?","start":2199.268,"stop":2200.404,"duration":1.14}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Form the locomotive stocks.","start":2200.404,"stop":2202.638,"duration":2.23},{"text":"And the lower court of the -- the lower court held that as a matter of Washington Law, the United States would not be responsible for the -- what happened on the railroad tracks because the railroad had an easement that under Washington Law, United -- the Government would not be liable, right?","start":2202.638,"stop":2225.608,"duration":22.97}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":2225.608,"stop":2226.404,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, here's -- here's what puzzle me about it.","start":2226.404,"stop":2229.458,"duration":3.05},{"text":"When I came to the briefs in the case that's following you, it seemed to me that there was a great question of facts as to what the precise relationship was between the United States and the railroad.","start":2229.458,"stop":2244.111,"duration":14.65},{"text":"Because your brief as does the brief of your adversaries and particularly in the other case, their reply brief refers to a lot of very long -- a long series of transactions or rather complicated series of transactions, none of them where in record here.","start":2244.111,"stop":2261.957,"duration":17.85},{"text":"There are matters of record apparently in the files but it occurred to me that before you reach -- before you can say that the lower court was right as to Washington Law in relation to the duty of the United States to this easement, there was a question of fact as to whether or not the relationship was that -- of the United States, was that of -- of a grantor of an easement and there was a question of fact that is out there.","start":2261.957,"stop":2293.154,"duration":31.2},{"text":"Now, that's my problem in a nutshell.","start":2293.154,"stop":2294.841,"duration":1.69}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Well -- well, Your Honor, the -- the briefs here, particularly in the reply brief was on hold, has raised that question emphatically, but I should like to point this out.","start":2294.841,"stop":2306.285,"duration":11.44},{"text":"That the Court of Appeals construed the allegations of this complaint and the representations of counsel made in their briefs and argument its meaning that the railroad had a railroad easement over the Government lands.","start":2306.285,"stop":2326.912,"duration":20.63},{"text":"As the railroad will -- on the dominant state and the position of the Government was that -- of the holder of a servient interstate.","start":2326.912,"stop":2335.337,"duration":8.43},{"text":"Now, the main thrust of the -- of the arguments in the main briefs of the appellants, both Arnhold and Rayonier presupposed that to be the fact.","start":2335.337,"stop":2348.964,"duration":13.63},{"text":"And I might say that no where in this amended complaints that Arnhold file -- filed four of them did they ever say the railroad operated a locomotive on tracks over the public domain.","start":2348.964,"stop":2366.835,"duration":17.87},{"text":"They alleged throughout.","start":2366.835,"stop":2368.931,"duration":2.1},{"text":"They -- they refer throughout their pleadings to a railroad right of way which in all the dictionaries is deemed equivalent to a railroad easement.","start":2368.931,"stop":2378.274,"duration":9.34},{"text":"Now having alleged there was right of way of the railroad across the Government property they -- they now submit that perhaps that that's wrong.","start":2378.274,"stop":2390.855,"duration":12.58},{"text":"Now, they did -- they did query it in the Court of Appeals that the main thrust to their argument there, in their briefs and argument and as it is here was that this was -- certainly, it was a railroad easement of right of way, one of the effects of that.","start":2390.855,"stop":2407.743,"duration":16.89},{"text":"Now obviously, this Court didn't take jurisdiction of these cases to pass on such a question as that.","start":2407.743,"stop":2416.2,"duration":8.46}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"A question that decide the point.","start":2416.2,"stop":2418.044,"duration":1.84},{"text":"If you -- at least -- I don't understand why you argue, the way you do in your brief and why you rely on the case by (Inaudible) a case that I happened to like very much (Inaudible) state which the law of negligence I know of, otherwise other aspects of the law.","start":2418.044,"stop":2436.489,"duration":18.45},{"text":"I don't see why the Government presents me with this brief.","start":2436.489,"stop":2439.413,"duration":2.92},{"text":"It makes me worry about the LeRoy case.","start":2439.413,"stop":2441.459,"duration":2.05},{"text":"Didn't you say all that is an important question?","start":2441.459,"stop":2443.194,"duration":1.74},{"text":"Let's get to the big (Inaudible) arbitrary to hold the Government liable for fire fighting?","start":2443.194,"stop":2448.378,"duration":5.18},{"text":"I don't understand that.","start":2448.378,"stop":2451.26,"duration":2.88}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor, let me go on with my argument and perhaps I'll be clear in argument than in the brief.","start":2451.26,"stop":2457.446,"duration":6.19},{"text":"I hope so.","start":2457.446,"stop":2457.763,"duration":0.32}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2457.763,"stop":2458.751,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"I would try to be.","start":2458.751,"stop":2461.486,"duration":2.73}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't like you to be led astray thinking this is nicely orderly private company case.","start":2461.486,"stop":2466.492,"duration":5.01},{"text":"And then I'm told I must decide with the fire fighting and the special unit.","start":2466.492,"stop":2471.899,"duration":5.41}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"But to conclude Justice Harlan on that point, we say you should take this case as the Court of Appeals construed the pleadings and as they interpreted the Washington Law.","start":2471.899,"stop":2485.238,"duration":13.34},{"text":"In accordance with your established policy which you would had to in numerous cases of -- of saying that decision of the -- of the Circuit judges particularly as in this case were one of those Circuit judges practiced for 40 years in the State of Washington, Judge Boldt, you should accept that.","start":2485.238,"stop":2508.098,"duration":22.86},{"text":"Now, the allegations of negligence here are -- are of importance.","start":2508.098,"stop":2516.869,"duration":8.77},{"text":"All of the negligent acts imputed to the Forest Service relate to the quantum of effort in fighting a fire.","start":2516.869,"stop":2526.998,"duration":10.13},{"text":"They are all negative acts of nonfeasance.","start":2526.998,"stop":2531.749,"duration":4.75},{"text":"There are no affirmative acts at all.","start":2531.749,"stop":2535.13,"duration":3.38},{"text":"They are not even acts as alleged negligence in getting equipment to the scene of the fire or taking up fire truck or a fire automobile having an access on the way.","start":2535.13,"stop":2550.419,"duration":15.29},{"text":"The allegations are that the Forest Service, although they conceive we put out five of these fires, they say the sixth fire got away from us.","start":2550.419,"stop":2561.299,"duration":10.88},{"text":"And we didn't use enough water and enough equipment and enough men to extinguish that fire before it leaves the plaintiff's property.","start":2561.299,"stop":2575.011,"duration":13.71},{"text":"Now, I'd like to point out, Your Honors, that this is the bedrock of the immunity, public fireman doctrine.","start":2575.011,"stop":2585.215,"duration":10.2},{"text":"In other words, there has been a distortion of that immunity in many state cases.","start":2585.215,"stop":2591.448,"duration":6.23},{"text":"I think it's been applied too far.","start":2591.448,"stop":2593.911,"duration":2.46},{"text":"It's been applied to some cases to the negligent operation of a fire truck on the way to the scene of a fire, but we are not dealing with that.","start":2593.911,"stop":2605.627,"duration":11.72},{"text":"We're dealing with the quantum of effort which we say should be clearly covered, and why?","start":2605.627,"stop":2612.562,"duration":6.93},{"text":"Because in the case of every fire, it can be charged if you use 10 men, you should have used 20 men.","start":2612.562,"stop":2621.511,"duration":8.95},{"text":"If you use 50 men, you should have been -- used a 100 men.","start":2621.511,"stop":2625.643,"duration":4.13},{"text":"And it is true that if we used more men and used more water and used more supplies, that fire would have been put out sooner.","start":2625.643,"stop":2637.927,"duration":12.28},{"text":"So, liability here on the ground that the immunity principle is inapplicable would mean litigation we think in the case of every fire that these people are fighting daily.","start":2637.927,"stop":2652.132,"duration":14.2}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"May I ask you if assuming what you said that the immunity does not apply with the statement of facts that you just referred to or just for finding of negligence, could you could then put out with more men and more water and so forth?","start":2652.132,"stop":2669.955,"duration":17.82},{"text":"You said that.","start":2669.955,"stop":2671.799,"duration":1.84}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I was generalizing, Your Honor, that that's true in any fire.","start":2671.799,"stop":2677.109,"duration":5.31},{"text":"All -- in any fire if you use more men and water --","start":2677.109,"stop":2680.72,"duration":3.61}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But I -- I --","start":2680.72,"stop":2681.427,"duration":0.71}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"-- if you're --","start":2681.427,"stop":2682.313,"duration":0.89}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I thought you said it could have been done, that you had -- you could have done it.","start":2682.313,"stop":2685.996,"duration":3.68}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I -- I wasn't talking about this specific fire, Your Honor.","start":2685.996,"stop":2688.978,"duration":2.98}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You weren't talking about the -- if -- the facts in this case?","start":2688.978,"stop":2690.884,"duration":1.91}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I was theorizing.","start":2690.884,"stop":2692.381,"duration":1.5}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2692.381,"stop":2692.77,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- that the charge that's made here is the charge that can be made in the 10,000 fires a year that we fight.","start":2692.77,"stop":2700.138,"duration":7.37}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if they could be proven I suppose and there's no immunity that might be enough to --","start":2700.138,"stop":2705.636,"duration":5.5}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":2705.636,"stop":2706.315,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- to find negligence?","start":2706.315,"stop":2708.499,"duration":2.18}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, yes.","start":2708.499,"stop":2709.176,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":2709.176,"stop":2709.733,"duration":0.56}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"If there's no immunity --","start":2709.733,"stop":2710.819,"duration":1.09}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":2710.819,"stop":2711.017,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"-- on as such a duty.","start":2711.017,"stop":2712.572,"duration":1.56},{"text":"It would mean that we're -- we're going to have litigation and a review by a court in the case of each of these fires.","start":2712.572,"stop":2720.334,"duration":7.76}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that the reason you think if there's immunity, the question is -- must be that it's reached?","start":2720.334,"stop":2726.343,"duration":6.01}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think it's clearly defined.","start":2726.343,"stop":2728.636,"duration":2.29},{"text":"Now, there's an aspect of it that Mr. Justice Frankfurter mentioned at the end, it may not be reached.","start":2728.636,"stop":2734.037,"duration":5.4},{"text":"And I'm coming to that in just a moment.","start":2734.037,"stop":2737.211,"duration":3.17}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":2737.211,"stop":2739.127,"duration":1.92}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not afraid to fire fight.","start":2739.127,"stop":2741.415,"duration":2.29}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"[Laughs] -- The appellant contends the Forest Service should be denied this public fireman immunity principle upon the following grounds.","start":2741.415,"stop":2752.663,"duration":11.25},{"text":"There are five.","start":2752.663,"stop":2753.998,"duration":1.34},{"text":"First, the Forest Service is primarily a caretaker of timberlands of the Government.","start":2753.998,"stop":2760.885,"duration":6.89},{"text":"Secondly, the Forest Service has many other extensive duties than fire fighting.","start":2760.885,"stop":2766.182,"duration":5.3},{"text":"Three, they refer to a cooperative agreement in their brief.","start":2766.182,"stop":2769.899,"duration":3.72},{"text":"And four, the Government was under a special statutory or common law duty under Washington Law to fight fires.","start":2769.899,"stop":2777.404,"duration":7.51},{"text":"And five, they say Indian Towing Company should be treated as overruling Dalehite.","start":2777.404,"stop":2782.217,"duration":4.81},{"text":"I like to just say a few words on each of this.","start":2782.217,"stop":2786.447,"duration":4.23}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Doub, may I ask you?","start":2786.447,"stop":2788.221,"duration":1.77},{"text":"Do I understand that the Government is drawing a distinction as regards the allegations between nonfeasance and affirmative in this issue?","start":2788.221,"stop":2798.21,"duration":9.99}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"No -- no -- no Your Honor.","start":2798.21,"stop":2801.115,"duration":2.9},{"text":"That's not involved here.","start":2801.115,"stop":2802.74,"duration":1.63},{"text":"I was emphasizing that all these allegations of negligence about fire fighting in these complaints go to the quantum of effort.","start":2802.74,"stop":2815.36,"duration":12.62}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What was that?","start":2815.36,"stop":2815.46,"duration":0.1}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"And they -- and they -- they are -- it is nonfeasance and there -- there is no affirmative acts.","start":2815.46,"stop":2822.374,"duration":6.91},{"text":"Now, I recognized that you can have in some cases an act of nonfeasance can be just dangerous as an affirmative act of negligence.","start":2822.374,"stop":2831.638,"duration":9.26},{"text":"But it's not just nonfeasance.","start":2831.638,"stop":2834.015,"duration":2.38},{"text":"It relates to the quantum of effort.","start":2834.015,"stop":2836.5,"duration":2.49},{"text":"And we say that that is the hardcore of the immunity --","start":2836.5,"stop":2841.09,"duration":4.59}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, does that -- does that apply as fully to subdivision (n) at page 29 failing to carryout and put into effect the fire suppression plan?","start":2841.09,"stop":2852.566,"duration":11.48},{"text":"I gather your adversary's description of that plan is active.","start":2852.566,"stop":2856.324,"duration":3.76}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, they don't define what the plan is, Your Honor.","start":2856.324,"stop":2858.939,"duration":2.61},{"text":"So, they don't even define what the plan is and I don't -- as I recall, they're maybe mistaken.","start":2858.939,"stop":2865.063,"duration":6.12}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I thought they have -- in the paragraph 18, this makes a reference to paragraph 18 which purports to give us a description of the plan.","start":2865.063,"stop":2875.374,"duration":10.31}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't -- I don't believe it does there, Mr. Justice Brennan.","start":2875.374,"stop":2878.645,"duration":3.27}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, in any event if there is a plan and that's what is embraced in this allegation of the kind that was described for us which I gather is the fact they -- the cooperative effort among all owners was the Government or otherwise.","start":2878.645,"stop":2897.376,"duration":18.73}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if it comes down to the fact that they -- that as described by Mr. Marion that everybody had list of people that were in the area working and where they could be reached and -- and what his point is, if we didn't call enough men --","start":2897.376,"stop":2914.947,"duration":17.57}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, he doesn't --","start":2914.947,"stop":2914.985,"duration":0.04}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"-- because of the fire --","start":2914.985,"stop":2916.091,"duration":1.11}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, he doesn't --","start":2916.091,"stop":2916.309,"duration":0.22}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"-- we call the men --","start":2916.309,"stop":2917.564,"duration":1.25}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's not his allegation.","start":2917.564,"stop":2918.912,"duration":1.35},{"text":"His -- the allegation is failing to carryout and put into effect the fire suppression plan.","start":2918.912,"stop":2925.627,"duration":6.72},{"text":"Now --","start":2925.627,"stop":2925.755,"duration":0.13}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Well -- well, in any event --","start":2925.755,"stop":2926.541,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, I -- I what I put -- I've been wondering is whether assuming that your characterization of the other allegations as merely allegations of supposed nonfeasance --","start":2926.541,"stop":2938.443,"duration":11.9}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2938.443,"stop":2938.81,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- omissions to do something --","start":2938.81,"stop":2940.108,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2940.108,"stop":2941.104,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- is accurate.","start":2941.104,"stop":2942.022,"duration":0.92},{"text":"Would it be as accurate of the allegation of failure to put to the effect the fire suppression plan, assuming now that the details of it is that Mr. Marion described them for us?","start":2942.022,"stop":2952.41,"duration":10.39}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I will -- I will --","start":2952.41,"stop":2953.079,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Would they not be entitled to an opportunity to prove of the extent under that allegation to which that plan had not been carried out?","start":2953.079,"stop":2961.989,"duration":8.91}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, we say that and we're still entitled to the immunity of public firemen if it's applied.","start":2961.989,"stop":2969.241,"duration":7.25},{"text":"The whole question is does the immunity apply?","start":2969.241,"stop":2971.974,"duration":2.73},{"text":"And that's what I'm directing my remarks to.","start":2971.974,"stop":2975.056,"duration":3.08},{"text":"Of course if it doesn't apply, they stated the case of negligence.","start":2975.056,"stop":2978.727,"duration":3.67}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what I'm trying to get to is would -- could the immunity apply, perhaps you're arguing the answer quickly, yes it would.","start":2978.727,"stop":2988.081,"duration":9.35},{"text":"If in fact, there existed that kind of plan and --","start":2988.081,"stop":2991.762,"duration":3.68}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I know.","start":2991.762,"stop":2992.618,"duration":0.86}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the Government backed down or failed to go through with it?","start":2992.618,"stop":2995.103,"duration":2.49}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2995.103,"stop":2995.373,"duration":0.27},{"text":"I would say the proper scope of the immunity principle would protect the Government from any charges and negligence as to its fire fighting activities.","start":2995.373,"stop":3005.557,"duration":10.18},{"text":"Allegations we fail to put plans and operation, we failed to use some other plans.","start":3005.557,"stop":3010.296,"duration":4.74}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Even though it had gone into such a plan with knowledge necessarily that those --","start":3010.296,"stop":3015.873,"duration":5.58}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":3015.873,"stop":3016.18,"duration":0.31}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- who joined with it would be relying upon the Government to do the things that the Government undertook thereby to do.","start":3016.18,"stop":3021.986,"duration":5.81}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":3021.986,"stop":3022.635,"duration":0.65},{"text":"And we rely on the traditional law of -- of all the states of this country and participated in --","start":3022.635,"stop":3029.537,"duration":6.9}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Of all?","start":3029.537,"stop":3030.525,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think so, Your Honor.","start":3030.525,"stop":3032.232,"duration":1.71},{"text":"I don't know --","start":3032.232,"stop":3033.06,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I think you might exclude one.","start":3033.06,"stop":3034.684,"duration":1.62}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, now, except one, and then the others that occurred, Your Honor.","start":3034.684,"stop":3038.654,"duration":3.97},{"text":"But my impression is that it is the established law in this country and municipality shall not be held liable for fire fighting that they shall be deemed in the operations of their fire departments and their efforts to suppress, discourage, immune from liability.","start":3038.654,"stop":3063.026,"duration":24.37},{"text":"And the basis of the reasoning was stated extremely well in Dalehite where -- where you sounded up and that you would not stating anything new, but the Court was stating what have been said time and time again.","start":3063.026,"stop":3084.168,"duration":21.14},{"text":"In Dalehite, you said the act did not create new causes of action where none existed before.","start":3084.168,"stop":3090.728,"duration":6.56},{"text":"It did not change the normal rule that an alleged failure of carelessness of public fireman does not create private actionable rights.","start":3090.728,"stop":3103.836,"duration":13.11},{"text":"And we went on to say to impose liability for the alleged nonfeasance of the Coast Guard would be like holding the United States liable in tort for failure to --","start":3103.836,"stop":3112.489,"duration":8.65}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that principle of your knowledge was -- have ever been applied to this kind of arrangement, this fire suppression command (Voice Overlap) --","start":3112.489,"stop":3119.425,"duration":6.94}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"This is the first time that a case has come up involving forest fire.","start":3119.425,"stop":3125.841,"duration":6.42}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, apart from that.","start":3125.841,"stop":3126.757,"duration":0.92},{"text":"I mean this kind of arrangement that under which --","start":3126.757,"stop":3129.701,"duration":2.94}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":3129.701,"stop":3130.26,"duration":0.56}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- for any other purpose --","start":3130.26,"stop":3130.709,"duration":0.45}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"No -- no, Your Honor.","start":3130.709,"stop":3131.637,"duration":0.93},{"text":"I don't think it has and knowing it has, the theory of those cases was --","start":3131.637,"stop":3135.836,"duration":4.2}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"We'll -- we'll recess now, Mr. Doub.","start":3135.836,"stop":3141.424,"duration":5.59}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you.","start":3141.424,"stop":3141.893,"duration":0.47}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument, Part 2: Rayonier Incorporated v. United States - December 04, 1956 (45)","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren4/oral_argument_audio/13250","transcript":[{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) 1924 authorize (Inaudible) Department of Agriculture which comprehends the prior service to enter into cooperative agreements with the States providing for fire protection.","start":0,"stop":18.278,"duration":18.28},{"text":"These complaints allege that this area involved here was covered by such a cooperative agreement to claim the United States and the State of Washington under which pursuant to this Federal Act, the United States agreed to provide fire protection for all state and private lands within the area.","start":18.278,"stop":45.758,"duration":27.48},{"text":"I emphasize that for two reasons, one, it manifest that the United States was not acting here merely as a private property owner, harvesting timber for profit as in the case of these plaintiffs.","start":45.758,"stop":64.166,"duration":18.41},{"text":"It was administering and acting in fighting this fire under the authority of the State of Washington as well as this Federal Act which authorize it.","start":64.166,"stop":77.857,"duration":13.69},{"text":"And the -- this cooperative agreement which is referred to in the complaint and which we filed with the clerk, explicitly provides that the personnel of the fire service are -- are clothed with the duties and privileges of state forest wardens.","start":77.857,"stop":99.523,"duration":21.67}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that this 45?","start":99.523,"stop":101.561,"duration":2.04}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":101.561,"stop":102.603,"duration":1.04},{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":102.603,"stop":103.366,"duration":0.76}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And where -- where were you reading from?","start":103.366,"stop":107.515,"duration":4.15}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't have it --","start":107.515,"stop":107.974,"duration":0.46}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's all right.","start":107.974,"stop":108.209,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"-- in front of me, Your Honor, but I think it's only a page or two and I think its right on the first page.","start":108.209,"stop":113.879,"duration":5.67},{"text":"It -- so we were acting in a dual capacity in fighting these fires, both as federal officers and as state officers.","start":113.879,"stop":123.456,"duration":9.58}]},{"speakerName":"Stanley Reed","textObjs":[{"text":"This area, I take it was covered by this.","start":123.456,"stop":125.717,"duration":2.26}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, it was and it's alleged in the complaints that it was.","start":125.717,"stop":133.733,"duration":8.02},{"text":"Now, I might say that you will find that that agreement, that cooperative agreement provides on -- in paragraph 13, \"The United States shall not be liable for any damage incident to cooperation hereunder.\"","start":133.733,"stop":153.51,"duration":19.78},{"text":"So the Government attempted to make it clear in its agreement with the State of Washington that it was not losing its traditional immunity.","start":153.51,"stop":167.929,"duration":14.42},{"text":"I think the only significance of that cooperative agreement is that it shows that the federal service was acting under the authority of the State of Washington and not merely as a volunteer.","start":167.929,"stop":183.659,"duration":15.73},{"text":"Another point made by the appellants is that we're not a public fireman because the fire service had many other extensive duties other than firefighting.","start":183.659,"stop":195.755,"duration":12.1},{"text":"Well, that I submit was disposed of Dalehite because the Coast Guard had many duties other than firefighting.","start":195.755,"stop":204.643,"duration":8.89},{"text":"Firefighting was actually one of the most insignificant functions of the Coast Guard, shipboard firefighting, whereas in our case, it's a primary function of the fire service.","start":204.643,"stop":219.711,"duration":15.07},{"text":"Yes, it has other duties but it's certainly far more of a major function than -- than that of the Coast Guard.","start":219.711,"stop":228.807,"duration":9.1},{"text":"So we say the quantum of effort directed to firefighting is too artificial a standard to be used for the definition of what is a public fireman.","start":228.807,"stop":243.731,"duration":14.92},{"text":"Now, that brings me to the --","start":243.731,"stop":246.101,"duration":2.37}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, Mr. Doub, I noticed in this agreement, you refer this to 13 which has the provision that the United States shall not be liable for any damage incident to cooperation hereunder.","start":246.101,"stop":257.885,"duration":11.78},{"text":"But what of Section 9, that nothing shall be understood to impair the right, the United States -- what State of Washington or any person or corporation to recover the cause of suppression in damages on the count of fires resulting from the negligent rule for unlawful act of any forest to the landowner or timber operator within the said protective units or any other person or the corporation, or to impair any other rights of similar nature under the Washington forestry laws under the federal laws or under general law.","start":257.885,"stop":288.674,"duration":30.79}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's right.","start":288.674,"stop":289.317,"duration":0.64},{"text":"In other words, it made it clear that it was not creating any new rights but it wasn't eliminating any existing rights that anyone might have.","start":289.317,"stop":303.678,"duration":14.36},{"text":"I think the first part of it, Your Honor, relates to a Washington statute permitting the recovery of cause in fighting fires against the private owner when he doesn't do it and the Forest Service of the State of Washington has -- state wardens have to come in and do it themselves.","start":303.678,"stop":326.187,"duration":22.51},{"text":"That's of course inapplicable.","start":326.187,"stop":328.15,"duration":1.96},{"text":"The latter part of it, we think obviously, is referring to the obligations of private property owners and not the obligations of either the State or the United States.","start":328.15,"stop":343.504,"duration":15.35},{"text":"Now, was the Government, as the property owner, under any special or common law duty under local Washington law to fight fires which might be deemed to destroy our firefighting immunity from liability?","start":343.504,"stop":364.344,"duration":20.84},{"text":"Now, I'd like to point out this difficulty of attempting to subject the United States to such a duty to fight fires under local law, which may vary from -- in each of the States.","start":364.344,"stop":378.993,"duration":14.65},{"text":"The fire service is not fighting fires because of local law.","start":378.993,"stop":386.051,"duration":7.06},{"text":"If local law makes a -- a private property owner and insurer, a guarantor, the quantum of our effort would be the same in that State, as it would be in a State where there's no liability at all.","start":386.051,"stop":402.21,"duration":16.16},{"text":"In other words, we're dealing here with a national organization operating under federal authority to preserve this great national treasure for the benefit of the people of the United States.","start":402.21,"stop":416.46,"duration":14.25},{"text":"We're not acting by a virtue of whether or not some individual state might have a firefighting law applicable to private property owners.","start":416.46,"stop":426.793,"duration":10.33},{"text":"Our position is entirely different, if the Court please.","start":426.793,"stop":430.305,"duration":3.51},{"text":"We are actually administering these enclaves of federal jurisdiction.","start":430.305,"stop":439.166,"duration":8.86},{"text":"We are -- we are applying and enforcing state and federal laws in this forest.","start":439.166,"stop":447.021,"duration":7.86},{"text":"Our -- the idea of these appellants and we're just another timber operator harvesting timber for profit as they are and subject to the same duties under state law.","start":447.021,"stop":461.602,"duration":14.58},{"text":"We say just it -- it cannot be sound and so we say immunity here.","start":461.602,"stop":468.393,"duration":6.79},{"text":"We either -- should be determine applying national basis that fire service in fighting fires should be deemed to be public fireman and entitled to immunity of such in their firefighting activities or it should not.","start":468.393,"stop":485.946,"duration":17.55},{"text":"But -- but the determination --","start":485.946,"stop":488.048,"duration":2.1}]},{"speakerName":"Stanley Reed","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't -- I don't follow you there.","start":488.048,"stop":489.648,"duration":1.6},{"text":"I don't understand.","start":489.648,"stop":491.596,"duration":1.95},{"text":"As I understand it, the Government has made it simply liable for its negligence, according to the law of the respective states, so it various in each place.","start":491.596,"stop":500.103,"duration":8.51},{"text":"Now, so far as you are firefighters and so far as you have the responsibility to protect them both, the national and state ground.","start":500.103,"stop":510.101,"duration":10},{"text":"I can understand your argument that the firefighters shouldn't be liable for negligence.","start":510.101,"stop":514.813,"duration":4.71},{"text":"But if – but if the – if there happen to be state law which said that you could not burn or slice timbers during the high wind, surely, the Government would be liable --","start":514.813,"stop":528.762,"duration":13.95}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Now -- now, that -- that comes to -- that's on the other aspect of the case, Your Honor, whether we -- whether we permitted a fire hazard on our property.","start":528.762,"stop":538.88,"duration":10.12},{"text":"I haven't reached that point.","start":538.88,"stop":540.111,"duration":1.23},{"text":"I'm merely talking now on the first aspect of the case that is whether the immunity of public fireman should be denied the fire service as to fighting fires or negligence in fighting fires or the failure to fight fires as aggressively as some plaintiff says, we should and stood by and did nothing to stop the fire and just relied on the United States to put it out before it got to their property as these plaintiffs apparently did.","start":540.111,"stop":577.108,"duration":37},{"text":"I say that our -- that immunity which you must determine whether it applies or does not apply is a much more comprehensive, broader policy than having its -- it depend merely upon whether there is a state statute imposing the duty upon private landowners to fight fires vigorously, as there was in the State of Washington.","start":577.108,"stop":606.685,"duration":29.58},{"text":"Now, because we're not fighting fires because of that local -- there's a local statute somewhere and if, as I said before, we're going to fight fires in the State where there isn't any statute at all and there's no obligation on private property owners to do it, just as vigorously as we would in a State that makes the private property owner a guarantor.","start":606.685,"stop":635.066,"duration":28.38},{"text":"Well, I see my time is -- did my time expire now?","start":635.066,"stop":638.996,"duration":3.93}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":638.996,"stop":639.454,"duration":0.46}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"May I ask just one question?","start":639.454,"stop":641.008,"duration":1.55}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":641.008,"stop":641.994,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I don't want to get in as another fact.","start":641.994,"stop":644.49,"duration":2.5},{"text":"If it takes long to answer, don't answer it.","start":644.49,"stop":646.378,"duration":1.89}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":646.378,"stop":646.737,"duration":0.36},{"text":"I suppose.","start":646.737,"stop":647.902,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"It -- it's your position that this exact complaint against the private landowner would show a cause of action under the laws of the State of Washington or would not?","start":647.902,"stop":661.524,"duration":13.62}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, my answer to that is this that as the allegations of this complaint have been interpreted by the Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit as the Washington law has been interpreted by the Court of Appeals, this would not state a complaint against a private person -- I mean a valid cause of action.","start":661.524,"stop":686.528,"duration":25}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument, Arnhold v. United States - December 04, 1956 (47)","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren4/oral_argument_audio/23702","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Number 47 Arthur A. Arnhold et al., Petitioners, versus United States of America.","start":0,"stop":13.622,"duration":13.62},{"text":"Mr. Ferguson.","start":13.622,"stop":15.893,"duration":2.27}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"If Your Honors please.","start":15.893,"stop":19.163,"duration":3.27},{"text":"The petitioners here are 23 families who reside in or near the town of Forks, Washington, this Northwest Corner to the State of Washington, and seven insurance companies who are subrogees for damages to homes and personal property destroyed by this forest fire as you've heard about in case 47.","start":19.163,"stop":45.081,"duration":25.92},{"text":"The action here was brought against the respondent, United States against the Port Angeles and Western Railroad and against Fibreboard Products Company as joint tortfeasors.","start":45.081,"stop":59.348,"duration":14.27},{"text":"The case against the other joint tortfeasors is at issue in the District Court in Seattle awaiting outcome to this appeal.","start":59.348,"stop":68.564,"duration":9.22},{"text":"The complaint charges the Railroad with negligence in connection with the origin of the fire, charges Fibreboard with negligence in connection with the escape of the fire on September 20th and charges the respondent here with a series of negligent and concurrently negligent acts, 17 in all in connection with the origin, spread and final escape of the fire.","start":68.564,"stop":96.315,"duration":27.75},{"text":"Those allegations are found in the record on pages 15 to 18 inclusive.","start":96.315,"stop":101.43,"duration":5.12}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Do they differ Mr. Ferguson on the -- from the (Voice Overlap) --","start":101.43,"stop":104.452,"duration":3.02}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"Not -- not in great detail.","start":104.452,"stop":106.248,"duration":1.8},{"text":"In general, they are approximately the same.","start":106.248,"stop":108.198,"duration":1.95},{"text":"They might -- might --","start":108.198,"stop":109.084,"duration":0.89}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Inclusive of the arrangement with the --","start":109.084,"stop":111.297,"duration":2.21}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"Of facts and present claims, yes, Your Honor.","start":111.297,"stop":114.117,"duration":2.82},{"text":"The appeal here is to review a judgment on the pleadings there having been an answer filed by the Government in this case which was filed before the decision in the Dalehite case I might say, and then a judgment granted on the pleadings after the decision came down in the Dalehite case which a lower court decision was affirmed in the Ninth Circuit.","start":114.117,"stop":138.909,"duration":24.79},{"text":"The petitioners here joined in and adopt the argument by Mr. Marion in Case Number 45.","start":138.909,"stop":146.858,"duration":7.95},{"text":"The complaint here briefly alleges that the fire started in the area owned by the United States.","start":146.858,"stop":155.789,"duration":8.93},{"text":"That the United States knew at the time of the combustible herbage, and old and rotten tires and had the right to abate the same but failed to require the abatement.","start":155.789,"stop":167.887,"duration":12.1},{"text":"The answer of the Government admits that it was the owner and alleges it notified the Railroad to remove these combustibles.","start":167.887,"stop":176.735,"duration":8.85},{"text":"The complaint also alleged that the U.S. both sold and traded in timber for a profit and managed and cared for its timberland where the fire started.","start":176.735,"stop":187.372,"duration":10.64},{"text":"The answer admits all of that allegation except it denied it acted for a profit.","start":187.372,"stop":193.886,"duration":6.51},{"text":"Now, the Government filed a cross-complaint in this case.","start":193.886,"stop":197.357,"duration":3.47},{"text":"They asked judgment over against the Railroad for everything found to be due to these petitioners.","start":197.357,"stop":203.694,"duration":6.34},{"text":"They asked for a judgment against the Railroad for $1,318,000 for lost timber.","start":203.694,"stop":209.964,"duration":6.27},{"text":"They asked for a judgment of $104,458 for wildlife and $140,070 for fighting the fire.","start":209.964,"stop":220.683,"duration":10.72},{"text":"This is not a noble or an unprecedented action in the State of Washington.","start":220.683,"stop":226.153,"duration":5.47},{"text":"The State of Washington's and Oregon, four states, there had been numerous cases of this sort.","start":226.153,"stop":235.62,"duration":9.47},{"text":"Private individuals, private corporations and municipal corporations if you please, have been held liable under the exact state of facts set out in these -- in this complaint.","start":235.62,"stop":251.308,"duration":15.69},{"text":"These cases and by the way the case law has been pretty well codified in Washington and also in Oregon today, these cases hold that there is a duty on a landowner to keep his premises in such condition as not to invite fire.","start":251.308,"stop":273.182,"duration":21.87},{"text":"And secondly, that if a fire does result from any cause, this includes trespassers from any cause, then the landowner must use due care to ex -- due care to extinguish this fire.","start":273.182,"stop":294.519,"duration":21.34},{"text":"There's a series of statutes -- that -- that are codified these rules of due care which are set out in our -- in the appendix of our brief.","start":294.519,"stop":305.839,"duration":11.32},{"text":"Now, counsel for the Government never has answered the question that Mr. Marion posed in this Court and in the Circuit Court.","start":305.839,"stop":317.15,"duration":11.31},{"text":"He answered it this way that the -- under the Circuit Court's findings, there wouldn't be any liability.","start":317.15,"stop":327.982,"duration":10.83},{"text":"I -- I'm going to come to that and I will call Your Honor's attention to it before the time.","start":327.982,"stop":335.409,"duration":7.43},{"text":"Counsel for the Government does not comment on or seek to distinguish these cases but says that they involve facts where the defendant was at fault in the origin of the fire or was owner of the land when the fire occurred.","start":335.409,"stop":353.007,"duration":17.6},{"text":"In general, that is a correct statement but it is precisely the situation presented in our pleadings.","start":353.007,"stop":361.787,"duration":8.78},{"text":"We contend that the Government was at fault in connection with the origin of the fire and we contend and plead that the Government was the owner of the property where the fire started.","start":361.787,"stop":374.435,"duration":12.65},{"text":"In addition, we have cited on pages 22 and 23 of the opening brief the case called Great Northern versus Oakley which was a case where a fire started on lands of another.","start":374.435,"stop":386.857,"duration":12.42},{"text":"It swept over the land that a receiver of a bankrupt company had a contract obligation to a big sludge.","start":386.857,"stop":395.996,"duration":9.14},{"text":"The Washington Court held in that case and has never been overruled that even though the fire did not start through any fault of the defendant or on lands owned by him, he had a right to abate this last confounded, commensurate duty on him to abate.","start":395.996,"stop":415.025,"duration":19.03},{"text":"Under the Washington Law cited in our brief and there's about 15 pages, the early part of our brief covering Washington Law in this subject.","start":415.025,"stop":424.503,"duration":9.48},{"text":"The Washington Law pertaining to a private landowner, the Washington Law pertaining to a municipal corporation, mind you, if the municipal corporation is dealing with its own lands.","start":424.503,"stop":436.461,"duration":11.96},{"text":"And a law pertaining the Washington cases, and there's two of them, where the fire has been started and controlled and managed by a fire warden, state fire warden, and in all of those instances appears in our brief, they have held the landowner liable.","start":436.461,"stop":454.23,"duration":17.77},{"text":"Under Washington Law --","start":454.23,"stop":455.487,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that -- is that by statute?","start":455.487,"stop":456.902,"duration":1.41}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- that is by statute and case law both, that's by statute and the statutes are set out.","start":456.902,"stop":463.768,"duration":6.87}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"In -- in your brief?","start":463.768,"stop":465.134,"duration":1.37}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"In our opening brief and the appendix.","start":465.134,"stop":467.56,"duration":2.43},{"text":"Under Washington Law, Rayonier or any private person would be liable under the facts pleaded.","start":467.56,"stop":474.593,"duration":7.03},{"text":"It's also clear that the town of Forks where these petitioners reside because this fire went to the town, burned about half the town and the wind blew -- wind blew -- changed directions at that time and saved the other half of the town.","start":474.593,"stop":489.215,"duration":14.62},{"text":"It's also clear that the town of Forks, that the town of Forks had owned the land where this fire had originally started six weeks before the catastrophe.","start":489.215,"stop":499.54,"duration":10.33},{"text":"The town of Forks would have been liable under these laws of -- that are -- the decisions of the States of Washington on (Inaudible).","start":499.54,"stop":508.017,"duration":8.48},{"text":"And that would be true even if the -- if the forest ranger here, Mr. Floe, had been a fire chief of that city and there we cite some fire chief cases with where a particularly one in the City of Toledo case where the -- that which happened in Oregon where the fire chief was in charge of the fire and the fire burned some third party buildings.","start":508.017,"stop":535.534,"duration":27.52},{"text":"So, we say to Your Honors that no matter how you compare this, whether you compare with a private individual, a private corporation or a municipal corporation, if you're going to use that test, the Government would be liable.","start":535.534,"stop":552.704,"duration":17.17},{"text":"Now the Government in the -- in an effort to avoid the effect of these decisions, takes the position that was a helpless Serbian owner under the Right of Way Act of 1875.","start":552.704,"stop":564.429,"duration":11.73},{"text":"This assumption is unwarranted where the complaint alleges and the answer admits ownership, control and unrestricted access.","start":564.429,"stop":572.898,"duration":8.47},{"text":"It is also unwarranted where this Court has previously held that a railroad can neither obtain a right of way across forest service lands that could not obtain a right -- a right of way across forest service lands under the 1875 Act.","start":572.898,"stop":592.357,"duration":19.46},{"text":"And I'm calling Your Honors attention to Chicago and Milwaukee versus United States, 244 U.S. at 351 which is in our opening brief on page 55.","start":592.357,"stop":602.232,"duration":9.88},{"text":"It is also contrary to the actual fact.","start":602.232,"stop":608.306,"duration":6.07},{"text":"The Government is asking this Court to adopt the Municipal Corporation Doctrine of Non-Liability for Fire Fighting as a judicially created exception of the Tort Claims Act.","start":608.306,"stop":621.308,"duration":13},{"text":"The Court should not adopt this theory for the following reasons.","start":621.308,"stop":625.354,"duration":4.05},{"text":"(1) Congress was aware of this liability whether they elected not to make a special exception.","start":625.354,"stop":633.483,"duration":8.13},{"text":"On pages 32 and 33 of our opening brief, we have listed a number of private bills where the -- where prior to the Tort Claims Act, Congress had acted to relieve negligence of the Government employees (Inaudible).","start":633.483,"stop":651.022,"duration":17.54},{"text":"In addition to that, Congress knew of the Bloedel Donovan versus United States case in the Court of Claims which this Court denied certiorari to which happened some -- just nine years to almost to the day before this fire in the same area, with the same ranger, under almost identical fire conditions and the Government was held liable in that case for the negligence of this same ranger.","start":651.022,"stop":677.834,"duration":26.81},{"text":"As this Court pointed out also in the Indian Towing case, the Federal Tort Claims Act touched the ground from under that doctrine.","start":677.834,"stop":687.809,"duration":9.98},{"text":"It is not self-defeating by covertly embedding the casuistries of municipal liability for torts.","start":687.809,"stop":698.036,"duration":10.23},{"text":"And thirdly, the Government has sought in the past and here seeks the status of a private person, in other words the Government here is not acting as a municipal corporation putting out a fire and not charging anybody for it in the complaint which is part of the record here to their answer in the cross-complaint, they are suing the Railroad for among other things that caused to putting this fire out.","start":698.036,"stop":727.283,"duration":29.25},{"text":"They have also in the Chesapeake, Ohio case and the Spokane International Railroad case, both of which are cited in the brief sued others for the cause of putting out the fire.","start":727.283,"stop":740.825,"duration":13.54},{"text":"This Court --","start":740.825,"stop":741.213,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you really -- really -- that advances the argument?","start":741.213,"stop":743.98,"duration":2.77}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"I do --","start":743.98,"stop":744.303,"duration":0.32}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"The Government -- the Government charges the cost of having adopted this (Inaudible) that the Government charges for filing to the (Inaudible)","start":744.303,"stop":756.129,"duration":11.83},{"text":"That doesn't make those agencies (Inaudible) the Government, that hasn't put him in the business to the sense for the businessman in business.","start":756.129,"stop":761.733,"duration":5.6}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Mr. Justice Frankfurter, this Court said in the Yellow Cab Case, 340 U.S. 543, that if the Government could sue a joint tortfeasor for contribution, it was liable to a joint tortfeasor for contribution.","start":761.733,"stop":779.154,"duration":17.42},{"text":"And my only point is this, Your Honor.","start":779.154,"stop":781.146,"duration":1.99}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not denying you conclusion.","start":781.146,"stop":783.009,"duration":1.86}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I'm not --","start":783.009,"stop":783.441,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) -- I don't like to have a bad reading for those conclusions.","start":783.441,"stop":790.11,"duration":6.67}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"My -- my position is this Your Honor, that if they are -- they are a private party when they want to bring this suit for damage to their timber or for fire fighting, they are not a public fireman when they are on the other side of a lawsuit, they've got to be (Inaudible).","start":790.11,"stop":809.217,"duration":19.11}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"What -- what is the statute to rely on, the Washington statute?","start":809.217,"stop":813.427,"duration":4.21}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"The Washington statutes.","start":813.427,"stop":814.961,"duration":1.53},{"text":"We have pleaded, as Your Honor will see in the --","start":814.961,"stop":819.829,"duration":4.87}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I have -- I have in here the appendix.","start":819.829,"stop":826.009,"duration":6.18}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"We have a matter of fact, we have pleaded the whole series of those Washington statutes that they are generally speaking --","start":826.009,"stop":834.432,"duration":8.42}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well they seem --","start":834.432,"stop":835.999,"duration":1.57}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"The -- they are standard of care statutes Your Honor, and they start with appendix 1, and there are series of statutes.","start":835.999,"stop":844.289,"duration":8.29},{"text":"We -- we are relying on all of them, Your Honor.","start":844.289,"stop":848.298,"duration":4.01}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"If any person shall kindle the fire on his own land to rely on that.","start":848.298,"stop":852.312,"duration":4.01}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we are not -- we are not saying here that -- that they actually went out and kindled them.","start":852.312,"stop":858.142,"duration":5.83},{"text":"But we are -- we are saying that these statutes and the case law that we have cited from Washington illustrate that this statutes are the standard of care applied by the courts in Washington and that even though they have held a person -- they have held a person for instance in Washington, under the same duty as that particular statute.","start":858.142,"stop":882.549,"duration":24.41},{"text":"If the fire was kindled by someone else even including a trespasser, he had reasonable duty after notice to put it out.","start":882.549,"stop":891.688,"duration":9.14},{"text":"That -- that is the point from it.","start":891.688,"stop":895.589,"duration":3.9},{"text":"I might say in passing in connection with the matter of suing for fire fighting cost, the cities historically, public firemen, that is, City Fire Departments do not so for that cost of putting out fire.","start":895.589,"stop":911.952,"duration":16.36},{"text":"But now even if this Court did decide to adopt the doctrine of public fireman, there is no excuse of emergency in this case.","start":911.952,"stop":921.009,"duration":9.06},{"text":"The Government had from August the 6th to September the 20th put this fire out to use due care, was in there -- was a very small smoldering fire at that time and that's one of the principal claims of negligence.","start":921.009,"stop":935.332,"duration":14.32},{"text":"And they had several years under the pleadings to abate the debris that caused the origin of the fire.","start":935.332,"stop":941.825,"duration":6.49},{"text":"Secondly, that courts have never excused municipal corporations for failure in the housekeeping functions.","start":941.825,"stop":948.828,"duration":7},{"text":"We cite cases in the brief for instance where there were defective floors in a fire station and things like that.","start":948.828,"stop":955.065,"duration":6.24},{"text":"This is housekeeping, this is prior to the origin of the fire.","start":955.065,"stop":959.503,"duration":4.44},{"text":"The New York cases are in conflict and in Steitz versus Beacon which is the one case cited in the Dalehite case on this matter, that Steitz versus Beacon case expressly recognized the exception which is where there's a statutory duty imposed on the person to put out the fire.","start":959.503,"stop":980.679,"duration":21.18},{"text":"And that is the situation that exists here.","start":980.679,"stop":984.962,"duration":4.28},{"text":"In addition to that, the Government has the benefit of the duties imposed by these statutes in common laws in Washington in protection of the timber owned and timberlands owned in Washington by the Government.","start":984.962,"stop":1001.205,"duration":16.24},{"text":"There is more land as it appears in the brief in private hands, forest lands and private hands than there is Government hands.","start":1001.205,"stop":1010.362,"duration":9.16},{"text":"And it's only fair that the Government should share its fair burden of these duties on the same basis.","start":1010.362,"stop":1019.276,"duration":8.91},{"text":"Now in connection with Dalehite, both the lower courts clearly based their decision on Dalehite.","start":1019.276,"stop":1026.459,"duration":7.18},{"text":"Both of these decisions were before the Indian Towing case.","start":1026.459,"stop":1029.814,"duration":3.36},{"text":"I'd like to just take a moment to point out the factual distinctions between this case and Dalehite.","start":1029.814,"stop":1037.202,"duration":7.39},{"text":"In the Dalehite case, there was no government property involved, the cargo in the ship were French property.","start":1037.202,"stop":1043.667,"duration":6.46},{"text":"In the instant case, it's Government property that's caught on fire.","start":1043.667,"stop":1047.023,"duration":3.36},{"text":"In the Dalehite case there was no duty.","start":1047.023,"stop":1049.535,"duration":2.51},{"text":"This Court and the Circuit Court found there was no duty of any kind on the Coast Guard and no duty was ever pointed out on the Coast Guard.","start":1049.535,"stop":1055.982,"duration":6.45},{"text":"In this case, there's a statutory and a common law duty on the Government from that property ownership.","start":1055.982,"stop":1062.599,"duration":6.62},{"text":"In the Dalehite case, the Coast Guard never fought the fire.","start":1062.599,"stop":1067.17,"duration":4.57},{"text":"In this case, they did fight the fire from the inception, that is they took control but they didn't fight it sufficiently we say.","start":1067.17,"stop":1075.888,"duration":8.72},{"text":"In the Dalehite case, there was an emergency.","start":1075.888,"stop":1078.887,"duration":3},{"text":"Mr. Justice Jackson's dissenting opinion shows that the explosion occurred less than one hour after the fire started.","start":1078.887,"stop":1086.76,"duration":7.87},{"text":"In this instance there were some 46 days, put it out, they could easily had been put out.","start":1086.76,"stop":1093.784,"duration":7.02},{"text":"In the Dalehite case, there was no notice shown that the Coast Guard even knew about the fire before the explosion.","start":1093.784,"stop":1101.854,"duration":8.07},{"text":"In this instance, they were notified immediately, took all the results notices.","start":1101.854,"stop":1106.534,"duration":4.68},{"text":"They certainly have plenty of notices.","start":1106.534,"stop":1108.409,"duration":1.88},{"text":"But the mostly important distinction of all, in the Dalehite case it was unprecedented that this fertilizer would explode.","start":1108.409,"stop":1118.088,"duration":9.68},{"text":"Nobody knew although they had been handling it for seven or eight or nine years that it would explode.","start":1118.088,"stop":1127.262,"duration":9.17},{"text":"It was unprecedented that it would explode but in a forest fire, the Supreme Court of Oregon said in speaking of -- in a statute very similar to one of the ones in our book, it is cited in our brief.","start":1127.262,"stop":1142.168,"duration":14.91},{"text":"The Supreme Court of Oregon said that there is nothing more dangers to the life and to property than a forest fire.","start":1142.168,"stop":1150.865,"duration":8.7},{"text":"I think that anyone who has lived in the West will realize that.","start":1150.865,"stop":1157.068,"duration":6.2},{"text":"Indian Towing rejects the municipal corporation law.","start":1157.068,"stop":1162.377,"duration":5.31},{"text":"Fire fighting immunity is at the heart of Municipal corporation -- of the municipal corporation exemption and should likewise be rejected.","start":1162.377,"stop":1171.713,"duration":9.34},{"text":"Now, the Circuit Court found that these statutes of Washington created liability without fault.","start":1171.713,"stop":1182.184,"duration":10.47},{"text":"The District Court didn't make any such findings.","start":1182.184,"stop":1185.739,"duration":3.56},{"text":"The Circuit Court did.","start":1185.739,"stop":1187.715,"duration":1.98},{"text":"The petitioners here have alleged a series of 17 acts of negligence on the part of the Government.","start":1187.715,"stop":1195.714,"duration":8},{"text":"The petitioners have not pleaded nor have they relied upon liability without faults.","start":1195.714,"stop":1202.711,"duration":7},{"text":"This Court has many times said, it does not decide hypothetical questions.","start":1202.711,"stop":1208.105,"duration":5.39},{"text":"We submit this is a hypothetical question.","start":1208.105,"stop":1212.036,"duration":3.93},{"text":"Those statutes in -- in our opening brief of Washington statutes have been construed on several occasions by the Supreme Court of Washington, the latest in 1955 in the Canyon Lumber case cited in the brief.","start":1212.036,"stop":1227.342,"duration":15.31},{"text":"The Supreme Court of Washington en banc in 1955 and just about two months or three months before the Circuit Court decision, which didn't refer to it or any other authority for its findings, held that that act was constitutional and was not liability without fault.","start":1227.342,"stop":1247.142,"duration":19.8},{"text":"We say that it is only a codification of the rules of the standard are fair.","start":1247.142,"stop":1253.949,"duration":6.81},{"text":"I believe that is a fair holding.","start":1253.949,"stop":1256.538,"duration":2.59},{"text":"If the Circuit Court decision is allowed to stand, it has defect upon the constitutionality of all of those fire statutes.","start":1256.538,"stop":1266.672,"duration":10.13},{"text":"The Government here has been confusing liability without fault with negligence per se, that in many cases under the Tort Claims Act in the 10 years since its passage whereby the Government has been held liable for breach of the statute or a city ordinance and on the bases of liability -- of negligence per se.","start":1266.672,"stop":1291.513,"duration":24.84},{"text":"On proximate cause, the Circuit Court held that the last of the Government's negligence acts that is the failure to extinguish the fire between August the 11th and September the 20th was the sole proximate cost of the fire.","start":1291.513,"stop":1309.437,"duration":17.92},{"text":"The Government did not plead this as an intervening cause.","start":1309.437,"stop":1314.381,"duration":4.94},{"text":"They accepted this as to wipe out the petitioner's claim against the Railroad which respondent says in its brief was this so -- was solely responsible for this damage and it also wipes out the Government's claim against the Railroad.","start":1314.381,"stop":1329.167,"duration":14.79},{"text":"The fire started on August the 6th, it was still the same fire when the damage was caused.","start":1329.167,"stop":1335.772,"duration":6.61},{"text":"California Court in Osborne versus Woody cited in our brief says, “A fire is one fire no matter how far it goes.”","start":1335.772,"stop":1343.786,"duration":8.01},{"text":"And the Minnesota Court said in Ferrell versus Minnesota, “A fire is the same fire even if it's joined by another fire.”","start":1343.786,"stop":1352.025,"duration":8.24},{"text":"Here there was a series of consecutive negligent acts by the same person, Mr. Floe, the forest ranger.","start":1352.025,"stop":1359.837,"duration":7.81},{"text":"They started with the housekeeping function which was permitting inflammable debris to accumulate on government land.","start":1359.837,"stop":1367.658,"duration":7.82},{"text":"At that time it was clear he was wearing his forester's hat.","start":1367.658,"stop":1372.472,"duration":4.81},{"text":"These negligent acts and with his failing to put out a fire in the 1600-acre estate and permitting the fire to escape, it was this same man wearing a fireman's hat.","start":1372.472,"stop":1385.194,"duration":12.72},{"text":"The effect of the Circuit Court decision is that Floe's negligence while wearing a fireman's hat was a superseding intervening cause and wiped out Floe's negligence in his forester's hat, or that Floe's own conduct was so unforeseeable that it necessarily intervened and this is holding this is a matter of law.","start":1385.194,"stop":1408.072,"duration":22.88},{"text":"This doctrine has never been adopted by any Court.","start":1408.072,"stop":1412.255,"duration":4.18},{"text":"It is contrary to the Washington Law which governed.","start":1412.255,"stop":1416.829,"duration":4.57},{"text":"Under Washington Law approximate cause is usually a question for the jury or the fact-finding.","start":1416.829,"stop":1423.323,"duration":6.49},{"text":"In Prince versus Chehalis cited in the brief, the Court said that with regard to fire cases and proximate cause said proximate cause is not the last act or the act nearest the injury, but one that actively aided in producing the injury.","start":1423.323,"stop":1440.922,"duration":17.6},{"text":"In the Theatre case cited in the brief, the Washington court held, another fire case, that a defective oil tank installed seven years before the accident was not superseded by the intervening negligence of the man filling that tank seven years later, that it was only a concurrent cause.","start":1440.922,"stop":1462.218,"duration":21.3},{"text":"And in the Poling case the Washington court held that even a subsequent criminal act in this was not an intervening cause.","start":1462.218,"stop":1470.891,"duration":8.67},{"text":"In that instance, they had come in the night, taken some plugs out of a fuel tank.","start":1470.891,"stop":1479.396,"duration":8.5},{"text":"This Court should use its power to correct these holdings or there will be a great injustice to these petitioners.","start":1479.396,"stop":1486.646,"duration":7.25},{"text":"There will be substantial loss to the Government on it's cross-complaint and it will confuse and conflict with the negligence law for the State of Washington.","start":1486.646,"stop":1497.291,"duration":10.64}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Ferguson, what -- what about the statement of the Court of Appeals on page 107 of your record, hence the Government is merely an adjoining landowner.","start":1497.291,"stop":1509.325,"duration":12.03}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, they arrived at that by this unusual method.","start":1509.325,"stop":1513.119,"duration":3.79},{"text":"The pleadings, both the complaint and the answer make it clear the Government is the owner of the land where the fire started.","start":1513.119,"stop":1520.112,"duration":6.99},{"text":"The opening brief in the -- in the --","start":1520.112,"stop":1522.376,"duration":2.26}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But the Court said that is under the control of the Railroad.","start":1522.376,"stop":1525.272,"duration":2.9}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"They held that, but as I pointed out, that's found absolutely contrary to the expressed statements to the complaint and the answer and your own holding in the Chicago Milwaukee case that I called here, placed both as a question of fact and a question of law if possible.","start":1525.272,"stop":1542.977,"duration":17.71},{"text":"That is just impossible when they arrived at that because there was something outside of the record.","start":1542.977,"stop":1548.085,"duration":5.11},{"text":"We didn't go outside the record but there was -- it's found outside of the record and they came to that conclusion.","start":1548.085,"stop":1554.423,"duration":6.34},{"text":"That happened to be incorrect.","start":1554.423,"stop":1556.059,"duration":1.64}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, is it -- am I right about this, there's a Washington statute that says where the dominant tenant has been actively looking after it then the servient tenant is excused?","start":1556.059,"stop":1568.341,"duration":12.28}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"No, there is nothing.","start":1568.341,"stop":1569.779,"duration":1.44},{"text":"There is nothing like (Voice Overlap) --","start":1569.779,"stop":1570.866,"duration":1.09}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Holdings of that.","start":1570.866,"stop":1571.616,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"There is no -- there are no holdings of any kind on the dominant or servient tenant is in the United States except one that I know of.","start":1571.616,"stop":1582.185,"duration":10.57},{"text":"And on that one which is cited in our brief and also cited by the Government, on -- in that one the third party who dropped suit against both the dominant and the servient tenant was allowed to recover against both of it.","start":1582.185,"stop":1602.028,"duration":19.84},{"text":"There was a suit over between the dominant and servient tenants but the -- the -- there is no such rule in Washington.","start":1602.028,"stop":1613.928,"duration":11.9}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But it -- it's particularly the sentence that I have read that the Government is merely an adjoining landowner.","start":1613.928,"stop":1620.594,"duration":6.67}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1620.594,"stop":1621.411,"duration":0.82},{"text":"They made an assumption --","start":1621.411,"stop":1622.521,"duration":1.11}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Which would take them out from under the statutes, I take it, that you (Voice Overlap) --","start":1622.521,"stop":1626.942,"duration":4.42}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- that's how the Circuit Court arrived at this conclusion plus approximate cause, Your Honor.","start":1626.942,"stop":1633.241,"duration":6.3}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if the -- if the law is that you have to put out all fires on your property, that's a different thing for putting out only those fires that you yourself start up.","start":1633.241,"stop":1642.624,"duration":9.38}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the law in Washington is this, it's a fact, if the fire starts on your property without your fault, you have to put it out or use reasonable care to put it out.","start":1642.624,"stop":1654.456,"duration":11.83},{"text":"Now if it -- you can't put it out by reasonable care there's no liability, that's the test.","start":1654.456,"stop":1659.397,"duration":4.94}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well then, why -- why did they use -- what's your explanation to the use of that sense by the Court?","start":1659.397,"stop":1664.954,"duration":5.56}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"Well my explanation of it is simply this, there was something outside of the record, they -- we did not try to answer it.","start":1664.954,"stop":1671.712,"duration":6.76},{"text":"We didn't try to clarify it, which we have done here but they adopted it.","start":1671.712,"stop":1680.11,"duration":8.4},{"text":"I would like to reserve anything for rebuttal.","start":1680.11,"stop":1681.99,"duration":1.88}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"You may.","start":1681.99,"stop":1684.53,"duration":2.54},{"text":"Mr. Doub.","start":1684.53,"stop":1686.496,"duration":1.97}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"If the Court please, Arnhold filed in the District Court four complaints.","start":1686.496,"stop":1695.647,"duration":9.15},{"text":"Now, the fourth amended complaint which is the one before Your Honors, which may -- we may assume did not understate this plaintiff's claim, states at page 6 of the record.","start":1695.647,"stop":1711.42,"duration":15.77},{"text":"And this is the only sentence about the origin of this fire, the last sentence on the page, “that said train threw sparks and fire into the dried grass, combustible herbage, and rotten tires both in and near the tracks causing the same to become ignited in at least six places in a distance of three miles.”","start":1711.42,"stop":1743.729,"duration":32.31},{"text":"Now, if you look at the proceeding paragraph, they described the Railroad operation on its right of way.","start":1743.729,"stop":1752.102,"duration":8.37},{"text":"They described the rotten tires allowing the road bed and quantities of dried grass and combustible herbage present on the right of way and between the tracks.","start":1752.102,"stop":1766.494,"duration":14.39},{"text":"And then they say then at the bottom, that the train threw sparks and fire into the dried grass, combustible herbage, and rotten tires both in and near the tracks.","start":1766.494,"stop":1776.998,"duration":10.5},{"text":"Now Your Honor, that was construed by the Court of Appeals as meaning the fire started on the right of way.","start":1776.998,"stop":1785.157,"duration":8.16},{"text":"But I make that logical and reasonable deduction, if these plaintiffs wanted to allege that this fire started on our adjoining public property, all they had to do is say so.","start":1785.157,"stop":1798.536,"duration":13.38}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, did -- was it necessary to allege that in order to have a cause of action?","start":1798.536,"stop":1804.359,"duration":5.82},{"text":"The reason I am asking because in the first statute cited by your opponent, every person who shall willfully or negligently set are failed to carefully guard or extinguish any fire on his own land.","start":1804.359,"stop":1821.308,"duration":16.95}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I'm going to talk about those statutes right now, Your Honor, but let me generalize a lot of things.","start":1821.308,"stop":1825.449,"duration":4.14}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) -- while you're talking about it, that is in Section 13 of the complaint.","start":1825.449,"stop":1832.348,"duration":6.9},{"text":"It seemed to me that there might be an allegation that it would be covered by that.","start":1832.348,"stop":1835.891,"duration":3.54}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, first we say that they have made out a factual situation here where the fire started on the right of way then spread to the public domain, then spread to a 1600-acre track of private property, and then on to the private property.","start":1835.891,"stop":1857.225,"duration":21.33},{"text":"Now, the -- we -- we interpret --","start":1857.225,"stop":1860.44,"duration":3.22}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) the Railroad's right of way to the plaintiff's?","start":1860.44,"stop":1863.207,"duration":2.77}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":1863.207,"stop":1863.899,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"It didn't go up to the Railroad right of way to the Government's property, it did that, didn't it?","start":1863.899,"stop":1867.117,"duration":3.22}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"It did, yes -- yes, the Government owned the adjoining property, if the Court please.","start":1867.117,"stop":1871.792,"duration":4.67},{"text":"Now, we've been unable to find any decision in the State of Washington holding that if a fire originates off your property, and then goes on to your property, that that property owner is under a duty to suppress it or is responsible for the condition of his property.","start":1871.792,"stop":1899.3,"duration":27.51},{"text":"In other words, you'll find that this Washington cases so far perhaps they will go that far in the future.","start":1899.3,"stop":1906.877,"duration":7.58},{"text":"But so far you'll find that each one deals with the situation where a property originated on the property of the defendant.","start":1906.877,"stop":1917.22,"duration":10.34},{"text":"The fire originated there.","start":1917.22,"stop":1919.668,"duration":2.45},{"text":"He either set it, kindled it or somebody else kindled it on alleged combustible condition that had been permitted to exist.","start":1919.668,"stop":1934.166,"duration":14.5},{"text":"Now, let me deal with these statutes.","start":1934.166,"stop":1939.902,"duration":5.74}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I -- I may say they all seem to be about applicable to be except the first one.","start":1939.902,"stop":1945.029,"duration":5.13}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the first one in my notes Your Honor is Section 5647.","start":1945.029,"stop":1952.695,"duration":7.67}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"It is Section 2523.","start":1952.695,"stop":1956.535,"duration":3.84}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Well first let me dispose the 5647 because that is the only statute of the State of Washington explicitly providing for civil liability and damages with respect to fire hazards.","start":1956.535,"stop":1972.79,"duration":16.25},{"text":"That's -- do you find that at page 79 of our brief Your Honor?","start":1972.79,"stop":1978.036,"duration":5.25}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":1978.036,"stop":1978.849,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"And that statute only applies by its terms where a person kindles a fire upon his own land.","start":1978.849,"stop":1986.629,"duration":7.78},{"text":"And that of course is defined in the dictionaries as meaning setting on fire, igniting and lighting the fire, so we are not under that statute because conceitedly this fire was started by an independent railroad.","start":1986.629,"stop":1999.842,"duration":13.21},{"text":"Now at Section 58 (1) (a) which is at page 81 of our brief doesn't provide for a civil remedy.","start":1999.842,"stop":2010.429,"duration":10.59},{"text":"It -- it refers -- it says that forests shall be protected and preserved from fire hazard caused by reason of the unusual quantity of falling timber upon such land.","start":2010.429,"stop":2023.545,"duration":13.12},{"text":"Well, that there's no charge as to that.","start":2023.545,"stop":2026.366,"duration":2.82},{"text":"Then it says it shall be unlawful for any person to do any act which shall expose any of the forest or timber upon such land to the hazard of fire.","start":2026.366,"stop":2039.342,"duration":12.98},{"text":"Well, we construe that is referring to an affirmative act of negligence.","start":2039.342,"stop":2045.18,"duration":5.84},{"text":"And there's no affirmative act of negligence here.","start":2045.18,"stop":2048.002,"duration":2.82},{"text":"As a matter of fact, these complaints don't even allege that the United States created any of these conditions about which they complained at all.","start":2048.002,"stop":2059.23,"duration":11.23},{"text":"We didn't -- they don't say we left slashings there, or cut the timber and that we left tires there.","start":2059.23,"stop":2069.614,"duration":10.38},{"text":"Then Section 5807, and that's the one that maybe applicable, provides that the owner of any land on the State covered wholly or in part by inflammable debris created by logging or other forest operations, land clearing or right of way clearing shall abate this condition.","start":2069.614,"stop":2095.386,"duration":25.77},{"text":"And it goes on to provide that the state may recover its cost, if the owner refuses or fails to do it after notice, and the State has to do it.","start":2095.386,"stop":2108.014,"duration":12.63},{"text":"Now the Courts of Washington as -- as we understand it, and I battle with deference to Mr. Ferguson because he is from there and I know he knows it greatly and more about it than I do but as we follow these cases, we can't find the Courts of Washington have ever held that this sections even create a civil remedy in damages for a violation.","start":2108.014,"stop":2133.744,"duration":25.73},{"text":"When Washington wanted to create a civil remedy in damages, it said so.","start":2133.744,"stop":2139.118,"duration":5.37},{"text":"And that and it did so explicitly on the first statute I referred to.","start":2139.118,"stop":2143.674,"duration":4.56},{"text":"And these next succeeding ones provide for a different type of sanction, and that sanction as a recovery of the state's cost.","start":2143.674,"stop":2152.597,"duration":8.92},{"text":"But in any event, Your Honor, we say this, the Court of Appeals has construed these statutes and they've construed them as being inapplicable.","start":2152.597,"stop":2162.617,"duration":10.02},{"text":"And we submit that this Court shouldn't be attempting to construe the state law of Washington.","start":2162.617,"stop":2170.873,"duration":8.26}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Doub -- Mr. Doub, I want to come back to a question and I think Mr. Justice Frankfurter asked you of the (Inaudible) of your last argument.","start":2170.873,"stop":2178.154,"duration":7.28},{"text":"If that's a fact and there could be no liability upon the private person in these circumstances.","start":2178.154,"stop":2183.849,"duration":5.7},{"text":"Then I gather under the Tort Claims Act it should be then upon the United States.","start":2183.849,"stop":2187.966,"duration":4.12}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, yes, Your Honor.","start":2187.966,"stop":2189.511,"duration":1.55}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And that would then answer the case without going into the question of fire fighter immunity, would it not?","start":2189.511,"stop":2199.63,"duration":10.12}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, perhaps -- perhaps you can take it off on that ground --","start":2199.63,"stop":2203.598,"duration":3.97}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) --","start":2203.598,"stop":2203.711,"duration":0.11}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"I hate to have a look and Justice Frankfurter to acquiesce in that because the Government is anxious to obtain a determination on this question of major --","start":2203.711,"stop":2212.955,"duration":9.24}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2212.955,"stop":2215.374,"duration":2.42}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"They have major consequence and that is the immunity of fire fighting principle.","start":2215.374,"stop":2220.091,"duration":4.72}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if I -- if I understand it, what the Government would like -- would be a statement from this Court that even if a private person might be liable in these circumstances under the laws of the State of Washington, nevertheless that this is a service as regards whose conduct there is an immunity notwithstanding the Tort Claims Act whether that's read in by way of exception or granted upon the Tort Claims Act or otherwise, is that right?","start":2220.091,"stop":2249.22,"duration":29.13}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2249.22,"stop":2249.584,"duration":0.36},{"text":"I think the fire fighting immunity doctrine is a question of -- except for one angle to it, it's a question of interpretation of the Federal Tort Claims Act.","start":2249.584,"stop":2265.267,"duration":15.68}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but the --","start":2265.267,"stop":2265.829,"duration":0.56}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Now --","start":2265.829,"stop":2266.027,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But the Tort Claims Act in words at least says that there is -- show liability of the United States, if a private person would be liable to the claimant in accordance with the law of the place where the act or omission occurred.","start":2266.027,"stop":2278.094,"duration":12.07}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":2278.094,"stop":2278.909,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, your point is, even if there should be liability upon a private person in this circumstance, nevertheless, we should ride into this so read into it, or find in it somehow an immunity in the case of fire fighters, federal fire fighters.","start":2278.909,"stop":2293.353,"duration":14.44}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"But Your Honor, I -- I think the case could go off on the ground --","start":2293.353,"stop":2296.326,"duration":2.97}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, but is that right?","start":2296.326,"stop":2298.156,"duration":1.83}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor, and -- and the case could go on as Justice Frankfurter suggested on the ground that the Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit which contains Judge Bone and who was a 40-year practitioner from the State of Washington.","start":2298.156,"stop":2316.647,"duration":18.49},{"text":"They have construed these statutes and they have held that under these particular circumstances, a private landowner would not be liable and that you -- you have to have a traditional policy of refusing to attempt to establish or create law for a state because after all it's not binding on the State.","start":2316.647,"stop":2337.4,"duration":20.75},{"text":"The Court of Appeals of Washington might not follow your speculation as to what it might be.","start":2337.4,"stop":2343.427,"duration":6.03},{"text":"And you have no decision in Washington that is directly applicable here to this situation.","start":2343.427,"stop":2350.629,"duration":7.2},{"text":"It may be they would hold the United States if -- where a private person liable under these conditions but they have never done so, so far.","start":2350.629,"stop":2359.564,"duration":8.93},{"text":"Restricted the civil liability in damages to a situation where the fire originated on the property of the defendant.","start":2359.564,"stop":2370.367,"duration":10.8},{"text":"And they have never held that it would apply otherwise.","start":2370.367,"stop":2375.73,"duration":5.36},{"text":"If I have a moment, I would like to make a one or two reflections that may not be pertinent on the Good Samaritan doctrine because it's of some interest and it's almost analogous here.","start":2375.73,"stop":2389.882,"duration":14.15},{"text":"You talk a good deal about it or it was there at least referred to in the Indian Towing Company case.","start":2389.882,"stop":2398.844,"duration":8.96},{"text":"You remember the idea and notion of the Good Samaritan doctrine is that assuming there's no obligation on your part to act, to rescue another.","start":2398.844,"stop":2410.242,"duration":11.4},{"text":"If you do act, you're under a duty to exercise reasonable care.","start":2410.242,"stop":2417.988,"duration":7.75},{"text":"Now, that samaritan doctrine is then a formative state, it's not even mentioned in the restatement on the Law of Torts.","start":2417.988,"stop":2429.409,"duration":11.42},{"text":"It was originated and as I recall it, by Justice Cardozo, when he was on the Court of Appeals of New York and it's been referred to by this Court.","start":2429.409,"stop":2443.298,"duration":13.89},{"text":"If it means that when the samaritan acts to effect to rescue, he is liable if he doesn't act strenuously enough, if he doesn't call for additional assistance louder, if he gives up as he swims and decides he can't make it, that he should have gone on.","start":2443.298,"stop":2473.646,"duration":30.35},{"text":"I say that's a very cynical doctrine.","start":2473.646,"stop":2477.641,"duration":3.99},{"text":"And I think because it penalizes voluntary gratuitous efforts which improper.","start":2477.641,"stop":2491.25,"duration":13.61},{"text":"If it means that the samaritan is driving some -- a victim or somebody he has rescued to a hospital and he goes through a red light or negligently operates his car with the result that that person is injured or another, of course he is liable.","start":2491.25,"stop":2510.563,"duration":19.31},{"text":"But I say that this -- this doctrine requires a far more consideration and definition than it's been given it.","start":2510.563,"stop":2520.179,"duration":9.62},{"text":"I think it could be a very dangerous cynical doctrine.","start":2520.179,"stop":2524.095,"duration":3.92},{"text":"We submit, if the Court please, the judgment should be affirmed.","start":2524.095,"stop":2530.313,"duration":6.22}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Ferguson.","start":2530.313,"stop":2531.503,"duration":1.19}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"If the Court please.","start":2531.503,"stop":2534.26,"duration":2.76},{"text":"We pleaded in our complaint that the Government owned the land where the fire started by that and we were specific about it.","start":2534.26,"stop":2544.894,"duration":10.63},{"text":"We meant the land where the Railroad was, the right of way, that is what the allegations and complaints say.","start":2544.894,"stop":2551.131,"duration":6.24},{"text":"We prepared proof to that allegation.","start":2551.131,"stop":2554.225,"duration":3.09},{"text":"So that is the way it stands at this moment.","start":2554.225,"stop":2557.373,"duration":3.15},{"text":"Counsel has mentioned the fact that he can't find a case where a fire originated on other property and then came to the property of another, the case in exactly in point is Great Northern versus Oakley where exactly that situation happened.","start":2557.373,"stop":2572.783,"duration":15.41},{"text":"But the fact to the matter is that that isn't the situation here.","start":2572.783,"stop":2576.185,"duration":3.4},{"text":"This fire started on property owned by the Government.","start":2576.185,"stop":2578.839,"duration":2.65},{"text":"That is what the pleadings say as what we meant them to say.","start":2578.839,"stop":2582.169,"duration":3.33},{"text":"There isn't any question about it to the fact.","start":2582.169,"stop":2584.344,"duration":2.18}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose they had done a 10-year lease on the property (Voice Overlap) --","start":2584.344,"stop":2588.029,"duration":3.68}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"We have --","start":2588.029,"stop":2589.011,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- Washington State law with the fact that they own and subject them to the latter.","start":2589.011,"stop":2592.667,"duration":3.66}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"Not unless they had a right of control.","start":2592.667,"stop":2595.204,"duration":2.54},{"text":"Under the Washington Law, if you own it and you do not have a right of control provided to do something about it after you know of the danger, then there's no liability.","start":2595.204,"stop":2606.508,"duration":11.3},{"text":"We do have a number of landlord and tenant cases, trackage agreement cases, licensee and licensor cases and they're all in our brief where they do hold that -- that there is a -- a right of control, a right to do something after notice, then there is liability, that's all.","start":2606.508,"stop":2624.264,"duration":17.76}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"How do you get away from the Court of Appeals' holding which seems to -- it seems to be a part of its holding, that the fire injury was not called by the original starting of the fire, that that was very remote.","start":2624.264,"stop":2639.847,"duration":15.58},{"text":"And that you had to look to what happened closer to the date the fire occurred, that the destructive fire occurred for which you make a suit.","start":2639.847,"stop":2648.87,"duration":9.02}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2648.87,"stop":2649.409,"duration":0.54},{"text":"Your Honor, that is the question of proximate cause.","start":2649.409,"stop":2653.72,"duration":4.31},{"text":"The -- the Circuit Court held, we believe improperly and it's one of the questions we presented here for certiorari, held improperly that a person, the same person can cause an intervening can -- can intervene his own negligence, that there's no authority for such and start any proposition in the Washington Law which is supposed to governed there.","start":2653.72,"stop":2677.397,"duration":23.68}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You stated -- you say that they decided the Washington Law rule there, do you?","start":2677.397,"stop":2681.476,"duration":4.08}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"We -- we say they decided not only Washington Law but the general law.","start":2681.476,"stop":2686.508,"duration":5.03},{"text":"There is no --","start":2686.508,"stop":2686.872,"duration":0.36}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"The negligence has to be governed if the liability has to be governed by state law.","start":2686.872,"stop":2691.606,"duration":4.73}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2691.606,"stop":2692.19,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Are we governed by a -- must we follow their holdings with reference to the point that I have just asked you about?","start":2692.19,"stop":2702.258,"duration":10.07}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't believe so, Your Honor.","start":2702.258,"stop":2703.883,"duration":1.63}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Why?","start":2703.883,"stop":2703.978,"duration":0.1}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"Not -- not when it -- when it is -- I think you have the right in your right of supervising, correcting mistakes, I think you have a right to correct a mistake as crucially erroneous as that one.","start":2703.978,"stop":2718.393,"duration":14.41}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But if -- and of -- that what I'm asking you is, must we determine that question by determining state law or federal law?","start":2718.393,"stop":2727.084,"duration":8.69},{"text":"Their holding that you could not attribute it in liability on account of the first part.","start":2727.084,"stop":2735.09,"duration":8.01}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think it would be a matter of state law, Your Honor, I'm afraid it would be a matter of state law.","start":2735.09,"stop":2740.074,"duration":4.98}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And they have held that under whatever law it does govern.","start":2740.074,"stop":2744.943,"duration":4.87},{"text":"There could be no liability for the starting of the fire.","start":2744.943,"stop":2747.328,"duration":2.38}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but they have held that Your Honor, contrary to state law which state -- was supposed to follow because the Tort Claims Act --","start":2747.328,"stop":2753.591,"duration":6.26}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Then we would have to reverse them on that point, wouldn't we, in order to decide in your favor?","start":2753.591,"stop":2758.951,"duration":5.36}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"On Your --","start":2758.951,"stop":2759.287,"duration":0.34}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"On that particular phase of your --","start":2759.287,"stop":2760.586,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"On that particular phase of it.","start":2760.586,"stop":2762.512,"duration":1.93},{"text":"You -- you would have to reverse them, the finding on our favor.","start":2762.512,"stop":2766.221,"duration":3.71},{"text":"That is correct.","start":2766.221,"stop":2766.778,"duration":0.56}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, if we go to the second part.","start":2766.778,"stop":2769.273,"duration":2.5}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2769.273,"stop":2769.351,"duration":0.08}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Page 6, how long was it made?","start":2769.351,"stop":2770.964,"duration":1.61},{"text":"How long as to which (Inaudible)","start":2770.964,"stop":2772.044,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there is -- there's only one fire Your Honor.","start":2772.044,"stop":2773.864,"duration":1.82}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand that.","start":2773.864,"stop":2774.423,"duration":0.56}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"It was a fire that started on August 6th then it went to August 11th and then it -- then it smoldered in a 1600-acre fire from August 11th to September the 20th which appeared roughly 40 days.","start":2774.423,"stop":2786.58,"duration":12.16}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Flared up again.","start":2786.58,"stop":2787.719,"duration":1.14}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2787.719,"stop":2788.164,"duration":0.45}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And if we -- if we -- if you have to depend on that new flaring up --","start":2788.164,"stop":2792.575,"duration":4.41}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2792.575,"stop":2792.647,"duration":0.07}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- in your complaint, what is the negligence?","start":2792.647,"stop":2795.743,"duration":3.1}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we -- we alleged out of the 17 acts of negligence, about 13 or 14 of them relates probably to that phase of it.","start":2795.743,"stop":2806.992,"duration":11.25},{"text":"That is negligence in failing to put the fire out, failing to use water, (Inaudible)","start":2806.992,"stop":2813.487,"duration":6.49}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That's where you rely on these statutes and if so forth to some extent to your statute on that or is that common law doctrine?","start":2813.487,"stop":2820.743,"duration":7.26}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":2820.743,"stop":2821.064,"duration":0.32}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Because that allows (Inaudible)","start":2821.064,"stop":2822.63,"duration":1.57}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"I would say primarily that is common law doctrine because at that point Your Honor, the fire has escaped now once from the Government land.","start":2822.63,"stop":2832.836,"duration":10.21},{"text":"It's escaped to a combination of government land and private land and they are in control at that point under a duty which you'll find in a Washington case as the duty of pursuing your -- if a fire escapes, you're supposed to pursue that fire.","start":2832.836,"stop":2848.68,"duration":15.84},{"text":"That is their situation at that point.","start":2848.68,"stop":2850.965,"duration":2.29},{"text":"They have pursued it but they have failed to put it out.","start":2850.965,"stop":2854.361,"duration":3.4},{"text":"And they have failed for instance the things we alleged at that point is that in spite of notice of decreasing humidity and northeast winds, they failed to use night patrols and that it did escape during the night.","start":2854.361,"stop":2869.258,"duration":14.9},{"text":"They failed to have a watchman or a lookout or anything of that sort to (Inaudible) it getting away.","start":2869.258,"stop":2873.909,"duration":4.65}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And what's the bases of your claim of a duty, is it the Good Samaritan doctrine at that point?","start":2873.909,"stop":2877.801,"duration":3.89}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, no.","start":2877.801,"stop":2878.982,"duration":1.18},{"text":"No, no.","start":2878.982,"stop":2879.681,"duration":0.7},{"text":"Our duty, that duty at that point --","start":2879.681,"stop":2881.239,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"At that point.","start":2881.239,"stop":2882.704,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"The duty at that point is a duty that is imposed by these statutes and our common law which was the duty to put it out before it escaped and before it escaped from your own land and if -- it does -- it do not do that.","start":2882.704,"stop":2898.862,"duration":16.16},{"text":"The duty extends to continue to fight it and continue to put it out before it causes someone damage.","start":2898.862,"stop":2904.526,"duration":5.66},{"text":"No damage had been caused in the first 40 days.","start":2904.526,"stop":2906.808,"duration":2.28},{"text":"All the damage took place after the 40 days.","start":2906.808,"stop":2910.322,"duration":3.51},{"text":"There is no damage here in the first part.","start":2910.322,"stop":2912.684,"duration":2.36}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Ferguson, may I ask?","start":2912.684,"stop":2914.079,"duration":1.39}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2914.079,"stop":2914.169,"duration":0.09}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Would you comment on Mr. Doub suggested that most of the statutes upon which you rely only one of them I think he said made any provision for civil liability.","start":2914.169,"stop":2925.368,"duration":11.2},{"text":"Most of them as an example in the case of 2523, provide a sanction of criminal sanction shall be guilty of a misdemeanor.","start":2925.368,"stop":2937.146,"duration":11.78},{"text":"And I gather this argument was that in that circumstance, these statutes are not really available to you.","start":2937.146,"stop":2943.845,"duration":6.7}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"It is.","start":2943.845,"stop":2944.314,"duration":0.47},{"text":"Would be alike the traffic light case Your Honor where a city passes an ordinance that is against the law to run through the traffic light, that you do run through the traffic light and you injure somebody, that person sues you and alleges that as part of the negligence.","start":2944.314,"stop":2958.831,"duration":14.52},{"text":"But on pages 12 to 23 of our opening brief, we have cited a number of Washington cases, there are also cases from other timber states where the same kind of statutes are considered where civil liability was held applicable.","start":2958.831,"stop":2979.855,"duration":21.02}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"In other words, these two established standard of care --","start":2979.855,"stop":2984.103,"duration":4.25}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"They do -- they do --","start":2984.103,"stop":2984.611,"duration":0.51}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- even though they make their own provision for a criminal responsibility and such?","start":2984.611,"stop":2988.924,"duration":4.31}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":2988.924,"stop":2989.572,"duration":0.65},{"text":"That -- that is the holding of most of the courts.","start":2989.572,"stop":2992.296,"duration":2.72}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That's the Court of Appeals' (Inaudible) to that.","start":2992.296,"stop":2995.882,"duration":3.59}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the Court of Appeals, you see, the Court of Appeals on that --","start":2995.882,"stop":2999.661,"duration":3.78}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"In the previous case (Inaudible)","start":2999.661,"stop":3003.34,"duration":3.68}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"No, the Court of Appeals didn't say that.","start":3003.34,"stop":3005.168,"duration":1.83},{"text":"The Court of Appeals eliminated that by saying that the last act was a proximate cause.","start":3005.168,"stop":3013.555,"duration":8.39},{"text":"That -- and that the last act that is, the escape of the fire the last time, the last time of escape, there's actually three escapes.","start":3013.555,"stop":3021.716,"duration":8.16},{"text":"But the last escape was a proximate cause, chopped it off there and said that at that time the Government, the same man was a public fireman.","start":3021.716,"stop":3030.041,"duration":8.33}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, why don't you discuss the statutes?","start":3030.041,"stop":3032.886,"duration":2.84}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3032.886,"stop":3033.17,"duration":0.28},{"text":"And held they were absolute liability statutes which would make them unconstitutional in Washington.","start":3033.17,"stop":3038.915,"duration":5.74},{"text":"That -- it said they were absolute liability statutes, certainly.","start":3038.915,"stop":3042.417,"duration":3.5}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) to turn to the opinion of the Court of Appeals --","start":3042.417,"stop":3047.729,"duration":5.31}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3047.729,"stop":3048.514,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- in which case purported to construe either decisional or statutory Washington Law, suppose I didn't care about them, the common law or the other in the states where -- what is it -- where is the utterance of the Court of Appeals which you say that this is wrong after which you invite us to consider Washington decisions which would prove the Court of Appeals is wrong.","start":3048.514,"stop":3077.487,"duration":28.97},{"text":"Just go through the text --","start":3077.487,"stop":3078.614,"duration":1.13}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3078.614,"stop":3078.903,"duration":0.29}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Then I'll -- I'll ask a question based on that.","start":3078.903,"stop":3079.815,"duration":0.91}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"I'll have -- I'll have to get it.","start":3079.815,"stop":3083.491,"duration":3.68}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Can I ask you a question, as you've told me, why isn't they wrong?","start":3083.491,"stop":3087.113,"duration":3.62},{"text":"Which -- which brief are you reading from, yours or the Arnhold record?","start":3087.113,"stop":3090.833,"duration":3.72}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm reading now from the Arnhold record --","start":3090.833,"stop":3093.378,"duration":2.55}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Page?","start":3093.378,"stop":3093.911,"duration":0.53}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"Page -- I think is -- it starts on page 79.","start":3093.911,"stop":3102.172,"duration":8.26}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"79, supposing the judge --","start":3102.172,"stop":3106.396,"duration":4.22}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3106.396,"stop":3107.166,"duration":0.77},{"text":"And now this by the way --","start":3107.166,"stop":3108.7,"duration":1.53}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"On this -- 79, I have no opinion.","start":3108.7,"stop":3111.647,"duration":2.95},{"text":"I've got a motion for judgment.","start":3111.647,"stop":3115.073,"duration":3.43}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, I should say it's Number 45, the record (Inaudible)","start":3115.073,"stop":3117.993,"duration":2.92}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Okay, all right, 79.","start":3117.993,"stop":3120.883,"duration":2.89}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm sorry.","start":3120.883,"stop":3120.996,"duration":0.11}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You're right on this?","start":3120.996,"stop":3122.877,"duration":1.88}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, Your Honor, keep in mind that in deciding this case the principal opinion was written in the Rayonier versus Arnhold case.","start":3122.877,"stop":3130.931,"duration":8.05}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Now --","start":3130.931,"stop":3131.129,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"So we -- we have to --","start":3131.129,"stop":3132.795,"duration":1.67}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3132.795,"stop":3135.393,"duration":2.6},{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":3135.393,"stop":3136.225,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, Your Honor --","start":3136.225,"stop":3137.27,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) the Court of Appeals in your view erroneously stated what is involved.","start":3137.27,"stop":3159.802,"duration":22.53}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, Your Honor will notice a start discussing Dalehite first and then I say they also mentioned the Feres case.","start":3159.802,"stop":3180.535,"duration":20.73},{"text":"Then they say that -- they'd go on to say that the control of complications of forest lands is much appropriate function.","start":3180.535,"stop":3187.582,"duration":7.05},{"text":"At that point they're still on federal law and they're -- they are deciding that -- this under the Dalehite case.","start":3187.582,"stop":3194.442,"duration":6.86},{"text":"There's no remedy here.","start":3194.442,"stop":3202.028,"duration":7.59},{"text":"And then they'd go on to say the Dalehite compels the conclusion that the Government --","start":3202.028,"stop":3208.729,"duration":6.7}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Where are you reading from?","start":3208.729,"stop":3209.558,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm now down at 83.","start":3209.558,"stop":3211.308,"duration":1.75}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":3211.308,"stop":3211.674,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"In our opinion, the Dalehite case compels the conclusion that the Government when intervening in the prevention and control of forest fires may not be said to assume the common law obligation of a volunteer.","start":3211.674,"stop":3224.625,"duration":12.95},{"text":"We do not regard United States had fire fighter agreement with the State of Washington undertaken to protect against forest fires as creating a distinction rendering the Dalehite case inapplicable.","start":3224.625,"stop":3237.244,"duration":12.62},{"text":"In entering into the agreement, even if it be considered a binding contract, the complaint falls short of alleging a binding contract and there is no allegation of consideration for the Government's promise.","start":3237.244,"stop":3249.456,"duration":12.21},{"text":"The Government did no more than undertake the reformed services in a public pass.","start":3249.456,"stop":3254.614,"duration":5.16},{"text":"I might say in connection with that, I think they are misconstruing at that point a federal statute because there are federal statutes which are in the brief pointing out that the consideration for that contract is, the state and private people putting up at least half -- one half of the money.","start":3254.614,"stop":3277.516,"duration":22.9},{"text":"It's a matter -- it's a consideration as a matter of law.","start":3277.516,"stop":3280.339,"duration":2.82},{"text":"And they go on to say having concluded that the alleged neglected a fireman to use reasonable methods to control the fire within the 1600-acre track was the proximate cause of this (Inaudible) fire to appellants' lands.","start":3280.339,"stop":3294.419,"duration":14.08},{"text":"And that in as much as the fire fighters where acting as public servants to the extent that their activities were without the area of the waiver of sovereign immunity contained in the Tort Claims Act, we might well conclude this but Rayonier makes other claims which we perceived discussed.","start":3294.419,"stop":3313.045,"duration":18.63},{"text":"Then, they say, the principal allegation relate to the failure of the Government to keep the Railroad right of way, the starting point of a fire and the adjoining public lands free and clear of inflammable materials.","start":3313.045,"stop":3327.987,"duration":14.94},{"text":"And once the fire started, they had to take precautions to extinguish it before it reached the 1600-acre track.","start":3327.987,"stop":3335.355,"duration":7.37},{"text":"Now at that point I say, they have misconstrued the rules of this Court and the rules of all federal courts by construing a complaint contrary to its terms, in other words, on a motion to dismiss or on a motion for judgment on the pleadings.","start":3335.355,"stop":3352.713,"duration":17.36},{"text":"The favored party, that is the person who has filed a complaint, the entire -- they have the inferences construed for him.","start":3352.713,"stop":3360.411,"duration":7.7},{"text":"Instead of that, they have con -- they have read in to it something that is absolutely contrary to its term and I say that they have made a error in federal law at that point.","start":3360.411,"stop":3370.762,"duration":10.35}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Some of these things bother me, I'm not terrified in disagreeing with them on the construction of federal statutes or disagree with them if they did what you just said, “We now construe your complaint most favorably or favorably to the complainant.”","start":3370.762,"stop":3386.959,"duration":16.2},{"text":"What I want specifically is where they purport (Inaudible) while they are concerned, there couldn't have difference to that on local law.","start":3386.959,"stop":3398.574,"duration":11.62}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3398.574,"stop":3398.941,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That is the (Inaudible)","start":3398.941,"stop":3400.863,"duration":1.92}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":3400.863,"stop":3401.37,"duration":0.51}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"It is my judgment against care as to what property law is.","start":3401.37,"stop":3404.296,"duration":2.93}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":3404.296,"stop":3404.896,"duration":0.6},{"text":"Then, next goes on to say it's alleged that liability may be predicated on the Government's failure to maintain the Railroad right of way in satisfactory condition.","start":3404.896,"stop":3416.075,"duration":11.18},{"text":"The rail -- the right of way held by the Railroad was at least to throw in to an easement and they cite Thompson on real property for that, but the fact to the matter is as pointed out in your Chicago Milwaukee case, it's not an easement it's a privilege.","start":3416.075,"stop":3437.116,"duration":21.04},{"text":"That was the Chicago Milwaukee case cited in our brief which was decided by this Court that there could not be an easement under these circumstances.","start":3437.116,"stop":3443.926,"duration":6.81},{"text":"Ordinarily, the servient estate is under no duty to make imperatives, the duty resting on the dominant tenant who alone is liable for injury to third parties.","start":3443.926,"stop":3453.118,"duration":9.19},{"text":"The allegation in the complaint that the Government had a right to enter and inspect the right of way does not -- does not alter this.","start":3453.118,"stop":3461.823,"duration":8.7},{"text":"Now, what they've done there has failed to take into consideration that we alleged absolute control rather than just a right to enter and inspect.","start":3461.823,"stop":3472.113,"duration":10.29},{"text":"Reservation of social right is not equivalent to an assumption of the obligation to refer and maintain the right of way.","start":3472.113,"stop":3478.287,"duration":6.17},{"text":"The servient tenant does not undertake to clean up such rabble as the Railroad may accumulate it.","start":3478.287,"stop":3484.069,"duration":5.78},{"text":"I say the mistake is in determining as a matter of federal law that there's a servient tenant in this case.","start":3484.069,"stop":3491.832,"duration":7.76},{"text":"The allegation is in the -- and the answer are both owner (Inaudible)","start":3491.832,"stop":3496.354,"duration":4.52}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"So just to that point --","start":3496.354,"stop":3497.671,"duration":1.32}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3497.671,"stop":3497.687,"duration":0.02}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"-- what you're really saying is there's an issue of fact between you and the Government as to what the nature of this relationship was?","start":3497.687,"stop":3504.18,"duration":6.49}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"Right, Your Honor.","start":3504.18,"stop":3505.217,"duration":1.04}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And therefore the -- until that issue of fact is predicated, the question of what the Washington -- is established, is cited, you can't tell what the question is that isn't -- arise under Washington law.","start":3505.217,"stop":3517.967,"duration":12.75}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"There isn't really any question of fact because we allege ownership and the Government admitted it in our case.","start":3517.967,"stop":3525.288,"duration":7.32},{"text":"The Rayonier case didn't get to answer but our case got to answer that if the -- it was plain, that it was alleged as ownership and it was alleged and admitted as ownership.","start":3525.288,"stop":3535.165,"duration":9.88},{"text":"There was no real question of fact but contrary to that, this Court found -- the Circuit Court found that it was a servient and dominant tenants which --","start":3535.165,"stop":3545.898,"duration":10.73}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Which you denied.","start":3545.898,"stop":3547.041,"duration":1.14}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"-- which wasn't mentioned in our brief and which wasn't argued in that Court.","start":3547.041,"stop":3555.172,"duration":8.13}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"May I ask you this, it's maybe one thing, you say they favored upon the plaintiffs, they favored upon state law is on page 80 at the bottom of the page.","start":3555.172,"stop":3565.118,"duration":9.95},{"text":"Look and see if that's right.","start":3565.118,"stop":3570.822,"duration":5.7},{"text":"While much is alleged and so forth.","start":3570.822,"stop":3574.013,"duration":3.19}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":3574.013,"stop":3575.395,"duration":1.38}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"While much is alleged is, their argument of the fire, negligence of the United States' failure to keep the Railroad right of way clear.","start":3575.395,"stop":3581.778,"duration":6.38},{"text":"I mean the fact of the matter as whether negligence in the failure to control the early spread of the fire.","start":3581.778,"stop":3586.189,"duration":4.41},{"text":"We read the amended complaint in its entirety, depicting a situation wherein the operation occurring after the fire had spread to the 1600-acre fire is determinative of the liability of the Government if any.","start":3586.189,"stop":3598.855,"duration":12.67}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that -- that would be -- that probably would be.","start":3598.855,"stop":3603.512,"duration":4.66}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But is it or not?","start":3603.512,"stop":3604.313,"duration":0.8},{"text":"I'm just asking.","start":3604.313,"stop":3605.654,"duration":1.34}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"I would say yes.","start":3605.654,"stop":3606.731,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But they don't.","start":3606.731,"stop":3607.573,"duration":0.84},{"text":"All I'm asking, is there (Inaudible)","start":3607.573,"stop":3610.225,"duration":2.65},{"text":"I was hoping that you would point out a case, a Washington case which they cite for positioning the case and would you say is wrong and then I was going to ask you, please give me the one occasion which you think prove that the citation is wrong.","start":3610.225,"stop":3632.08,"duration":21.86}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3632.08,"stop":3632.524,"duration":0.44},{"text":"But unfortunately Your Honor, they didn't cite a Washington case.","start":3632.524,"stop":3635.928,"duration":3.4}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, then -- they didn't cite -- having cited these -- state as Washington Law, did they state a proposition of law purporting that it was Washington Law, which you say is demonstrable not Washington Law.","start":3635.928,"stop":3650.408,"duration":14.48}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, all right I can --","start":3650.408,"stop":3651.352,"duration":0.94}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"How can you do that?","start":3651.352,"stop":3652.205,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"I can give you that.","start":3652.205,"stop":3653.311,"duration":1.11}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right, let's have that.","start":3653.311,"stop":3655.576,"duration":2.26}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"On page -- looking for this in -- I'm looking for this liability without fault, unfortunately (Inaudible)","start":3655.576,"stop":3686.906,"duration":31.33},{"text":"It's right at the end.","start":3686.906,"stop":3688.687,"duration":1.78}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That puts the question (Inaudible)","start":3688.687,"stop":3691.791,"duration":3.1}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Perhaps Mr. Ferguson, you could give us a memo on -- a memorandum on that?","start":3691.791,"stop":3696.299,"duration":4.51}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3696.299,"stop":3696.712,"duration":0.41},{"text":"Would be very glad to, Your Honor.","start":3696.712,"stop":3697.92,"duration":1.21}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Point -- point those parts out that Mr. Justice Frankfurter has asked about, just give us a list of the cases that you -- you believe contradict that, then counsel may -- the counsel may reply to it.","start":3697.92,"stop":3711.613,"duration":13.69}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"I'd be very happy --","start":3711.613,"stop":3712.139,"duration":0.53}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Do that -- and do that promptly, please.","start":3712.139,"stop":3714.32,"duration":2.18},{"text":"Please do so.","start":3714.32,"stop":3714.422,"duration":0.1}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":3714.422,"stop":3715.768,"duration":1.35}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes?","start":3715.768,"stop":3716.273,"duration":0.51}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"May I add to that on page 107 of your record, your case.","start":3716.273,"stop":3722.05,"duration":5.78}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, in -- in our case.","start":3722.05,"stop":3726.881,"duration":4.83}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"About halfway down the page, hence the Government was merely an adjoining landowner, and that a fire started by another, subject to the spread, and have no duty to follow the fire.","start":3726.881,"stop":3740.282,"duration":13.4},{"text":"Well that's what the Court of Appeals have said in your case.","start":3740.282,"stop":3743.339,"duration":3.06}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3743.339,"stop":3743.937,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, is that right or wrong and what cases support or attack?","start":3743.937,"stop":3749.096,"duration":5.16}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"You want us to put us that in our memo also, fine.","start":3749.096,"stop":3752.622,"duration":3.53}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"The Chief Justice (Inaudible)","start":3752.622,"stop":3753.718,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Briefly, do you think the propositions (Inaudible) they said -- that they've put under which is not (Inaudible) two cases are enough, they're really destructive.","start":3753.718,"stop":3763.426,"duration":9.71},{"text":"But the reason being that on the hope, a very good reading, this Court again exercised an independent judgment on local law of Washington to get a decision and this conflict say, that which the Court of Appeals purported to give its local law is clearly not local.","start":3763.426,"stop":3782.663,"duration":19.24}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3782.663,"stop":3784.055,"duration":1.39}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That is -- going to say they have -- there is -- (Inaudible) to go into the (Inaudible) law which Washington law would probably get lost in that part (Inaudible)","start":3784.055,"stop":3794.154,"duration":10.1}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Ferguson","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":3794.154,"stop":3797.286,"duration":3.13}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Warren Court","arguedOn":"Dec 4, 1956","petitioner":"Rayonier Incorporated","respondent":"United States","docket":"45","citation":"352 US 315 (1957)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/352/315","lowerCourt":"United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"Jan 28, 1957"}